# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A **501(c) organization** is a nonprofit organization in the federal law of the United States according to Internal Revenue Code (26 U.S.C. § 501(c)).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Such organizations are exempt from some federal income taxes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Sections 503 through 505 set out the requirements for obtaining such exemptions.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Many states refer to Section 501(c) for definitions of organizations exempt from state taxation as well.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] 501(c) organizations can receive unlimited contributions from individuals, corporations, and unions.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] For example, a nonprofit organization may be tax-exempt under section 501(c)(3) if its primary activities are charitable, religious, educational, scientific, literary, testing for public safety, fostering amateur sports competition, or preventing cruelty to children or animals.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] According to the IRS Publication 557, in the *Organization Reference Chart* section, the following is an exact list of 501(c) organization types (29 in total) and their corresponding descriptions.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A 501(c) organization is subject to tax on its unrelated business income.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] For most organizations, an organization's activity generates unrelated business income if it is regularly carried on and it is not substantially related to furthering the exempt purpose of the organization.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Disposal of donated goods valued over $2,500, or acceptance of goods worth over $5,000 may trigger special filing and record-keeping requirements.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A 501(c) organization must maintain proper records and file certain annual or special-purpose tax returns, e.g., 26 U.S.C. § 6033 and 26 U.S.C. § 6050L.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Prior to 2008, an annual return was not generally required from an exempt organization with less than $25,000 in gross income yearly.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Since 2008, most organizations whose annual gross receipts are less than $50,000 must file an annual information return known as Form 990-N.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Form 990-N, Form 990, Form 990-EZ, and Form 990-PF must be submitted electronically.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Failure to file required returns such as Form 990 (Return of Organization Exempt From Income Tax) may result in fines of up to $250,000 per year.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Exempt or political organizations, excluding churches or similar religious entities, must make their returns, reports, notices, and exempt applications available for public inspection.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Form 4506-A also allows the public inspection or photocopying access to Form 1023 "Application for Recognition of Exemption" or Form 1024, Form 8871 "Political Organization Notice of Section 527 Status", and Form 8872 "Political Organization Report of Contribution and Expenditures".
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Internet access to many organizations' 990 and some other forms are available through GuideStar.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Failure to file such timely returns and to make other specific information available to the public also is prohibited.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Between 2010 and 2017 the IRS revoked the nonprofit status of more than 760,000 nonprofit organizations for failing to file the 990 form.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The 501(c)(3) exemption also applies for any unincorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association, or foundation that is organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as "Friends of" organizations.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] 26 U.S.C. § 170, provides a deduction, for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Organizations described in section 501(c)(3) are prohibited from conducting political campaign activities to intervene in elections to public office.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] On the other hand, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Although the law states that "No substantial part..." of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities may register for a 501(h) election allowing them to lawfully conduct lobbying activities as long as their financial expenditure does not exceed a specified amount.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of tax exempt status if any of these rules are violated.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to conduct some or all of its charitable activities outside the United States.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Donors' contributions to a 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible only if the contribution is for the use of the 501(c)(3) organization, and that the 501(c)(3) organization is not merely serving as an agent or conduit of a foreign charitable organization.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A **501(c)(4) organization** is a social welfare organization, such as a civic organization or a neighborhood association.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] An organization is considered by the IRS to be operated exclusively for the promotion of social welfare if it is primarily engaged in promoting the common good and general welfare of the people of the community.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Net earnings must be exclusively used for charitable, educational, or recreational purposes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] 501(c)(4)s are similar to 501(c)(5)s and 501(c)(6)s in that the organizations may inform the public on controversial subjects and attempt to influence legislation relevant to its program.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Unlike 501(c)(3) organizations, they may also participate in political campaigns and elections, as long as their primary activity is the promotion of social welfare and related to the organization's purpose.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The income tax exemption for 501(c)(4) organizations applies to most of their operations, but income spent on political activities—generally the advocacy of a particular candidate in an election—is taxable.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] An "action" organization generally qualifies as a 501(c)(4) organization.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] An "action" organization is one whose activities substantially include, or are exclusively, direct or grassroots lobbying related to advocacy for or against legislation or proposing, supporting, or opposing legislation that is related to its purpose.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A 501(c)(4) organization may directly or indirectly support or oppose a candidate for public office as long as such activities are not a substantial amount of its activities.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A 501(c)(4) organization that lobbies must register with the Clerk of the House if it lobbies members of the House or their staff.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Likewise, a 501(c)(4) organization must register with the Secretary of the Senate if it lobbies members of the Senate or their staff.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] In addition, the 501(c)(4) organization must either inform its members the amount it spends on lobbying or pay a proxy tax to the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Lobbying expenses and political expenses are not deductible as business expenses.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Wisconsin Right to Life, Inc.*, in which the Supreme Court struck down the part of the McCain-Feingold Act that prohibited 501(c)(4)s, 501(c)(5)s, and 501(c)(6)s from broadcasting electioneering communications.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The Act defined an electioneering communication as a communication that mentions a candidate's name 60 days before a primary or 30 days before a general election.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Contributions to 501(c)(4) organizations are not tax-deductible as charitable donations unless the organization is either a volunteer fire department or a veterans organization.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Dues or contributions to 501(c)(4) organizations may be deductible as a business expense under IRC 162, although amounts paid for intervention or participation in any political campaign, direct lobbying, grass roots lobbying, and contact with certain federal officials are not deductible.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] If a 501(c)(4) engages in a substantial number of these activities, then only the amount of dues or contributions that can be attributed to other activities may be deductible as a business expense.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The organization must provide a notice to its members containing a reasonable estimate of the amount related to lobbying and political campaign expenditures, or else it is subject to a proxy tax on its lobbying and political campaign expenditures.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] It must also state that contributions to the organization are not deductible as charitable contributions during fundraising.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A 501(c)(4) organization is not required to disclose their donors publicly, with the exception of organizations that make independent expenditures as of 2018.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The former complete lack of disclosure led to extensive use of the 501(c)(4) provisions for organizations that are actively involved in lobbying, and has become controversial.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Criticized as "dark money", spending from these organizations on political advertisements has exceeded spending from Super PACs.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Spending by organizations that do not disclose their donors increased from less than $5.2 million in 2006 to well over $300 million during the 2012 election season.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The origins of 501(c)(4) organizations date back to the Revenue Act of 1913, which created a new group of tax-exempt organizations dedicated to social welfare in a precursor to what is now Internal Revenue Code Section 501(c)(4).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The Protecting Americans from Tax Hikes Act of 2015 introduced a new requirement on 501(c)(4) organizations.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Within 60 days of the organization's formation, a 501(c)(4) organization is required to file Form 8976 with the Internal Revenue Service as notification that it is operating as a section 501(c)(4) organization.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The Internal Revenue Service will acknowledge receipt of the notification, but the acknowledgment is not a determination that the organization qualifies for section 501(c)(4) tax-exempt status.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A 501(c)(4) organization is not required to send the notification if the organization was formed on or before July 8, 2016, and it either applied for a determination letter using Form 1024 or filed a Form 990 between December 19, 2015, and July 8, 2016.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] As of January 2018, the application for recognition of exemption as a 501(c)(4) organization is a new form, Form 1024-A, rather than Form 1024.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] In 2017 revocations of 501(c)(4) groups comprised 58% which usually is only 15% of the total nonprofits which have their tax status revoked by the IRS for their failure to file Form 990.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A **501(c)(5) organization** is a labor organization, an agricultural organization, or a horticultural organization.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Labor unions, county fairs, and flower societies are examples of these types of groups.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Labor union organizations were a primary benefactor of this organization type, dating to the 19th century.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] According to the Internal Revenue Service, a 501(c)(5) organization has a duty of providing service to its members first.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The organization's benefits may not inure to a specific member, but the rules for inurement vary among the three different types of organizations under this segment.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A 501(c)(5) organization can make unlimited corporate, individual, or union contributions.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A labor organization may pay benefits to its members because paying benefits improves all members' shared working conditions.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] An agricultural organization can provide financial assistance to its members in order to improve the conditions of those engaged in agricultural pursuits generally.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Members can benefit in incidental ways from the organization's exempt activities as long as the benefits are available to all persons.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The first exemption for labor organizations from corporate income tax was enacted as part of the Payne–Aldrich Tariff Act of 1909.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The Revenue Act of 1913 excluded "labor, agricultural, or horticultural organizations" from income tax liability.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Much like 501(c)(4) and 501(c)(6) organizations, 501(c)(5) organizations may also perform some political activities.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] 501(c)(5) organizations are allowed to attempt to influence legislation that is related to the common union interests of its members.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] 501(c)(5) organizations can receive unlimited contributions from corporations, individuals, and labor unions.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The names and addresses of contributors are not required to be made available for public inspection.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] All other information, including the amount of contributions, the description of noncash contributions, and any other information, is required to be made available for public inspection unless it clearly identifies the contributor.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A union membership dues paid to a 501(c)(5) organization are generally an ordinary and necessary business expense.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The membership dues are tax-deductible in full unless a substantial part of the 501(c)(5) organization's activities consists of political activity, in which case a tax deduction is allowed only for the portion of membership dues that are for other activities.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The Federal Election Commission is required to enforce this provision based on a federal court decision in 2018.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A **501(c)(6) organization** is a business league, a chamber of commerce like the U.S.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A business league may qualify if it is an association of persons having a common business interest, whose purpose is to promote the common business interest and whose activities improve business conditions rather than actually conduct the business itself.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Members of the organization must be of the same trade, business, occupation, or profession in order to qualify.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A local chamber of commerce or board of trade could qualify for similar reasons except that they may promote the common economic interests of all the commercial enterprises in a given trade or community.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] In order to qualify for a tax-exemption under section 501(c)(6), the organization must specify that it seeks to promote and improve business condition for a specific type of business.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Improving business conditions for *all* types of businesses is not generally qualifying.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Similarly, providing a service for a specific type of business is also not typically qualifying, as that would usually be more of a commercial enterprise.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] For example, the service of managing health insurance plans for its member businesses is often a commercial enterprise if it is not substantially related to improving the business conditions for specific lines of businesses.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] An association that promotes the common interests of certain hobbyists would not qualify because the Internal Revenue Service does not consider hobbies to be activities conducted as businesses.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] An organization whose primary activity is advertising the products or services of its members does not qualify because the organization is performing a service for its members rather than promoting common interests.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] If an organization's primary activity is advertising the products or services of its members' industry as a whole, however, the organization will generally qualify if it also performs other services for its members.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Much like 501(c)(4) and 501(c)(5) organizations, 501(c)(6) organizations may also perform some political activities.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] 501(c)(6) organizations are allowed to attempt to influence legislation that is related to the common business interests of its members.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A 501(c)(6) organization may receive unlimited contributions from corporations, individuals, and labor unions.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The names and addresses of contributors are not required to be made available for public inspection, with the exception of a 501(c)(6) organization that makes independent expenditures.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] All other information, including the amount of contributions, the description of non-cash contributions, and any other information, is required to be made available for public inspection unless it clearly identifies the contributor.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Chamber of Commerce is a large political spender, and Freedom Partners used its status as a 501(c)(6) organization to raise and distribute over $250 million during the 2012 election campaigns without disclosing its donors.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The group's existence was not publicly known until nearly a year after the election.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A business's membership dues paid to a 501(c)(6) organization are generally an ordinary and necessary business expense.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The membership dues are tax-deductible in full unless a substantial part of the 501(c)(6) organization's activities consists of political activity, in which case a tax deduction is allowed only for the portion of membership dues that are for other activities.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The predecessor of IRC 501(c)(6) was enacted as part of the Revenue Act of 1913 likely due to a U.S.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Chamber of Commerce request for an exemption for nonprofit "civic" and "commercial" organizations, which resulted in IRC 501(c)(4) for nonprofit "civic" organizations and IRC 501(c)(6) for nonprofit "commercially-oriented" organizations.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The Revenue Act of 1928 amended the statute to include real estate boards.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] In 1966, professional football leagues were added to the described organizations.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] IRC 501(c)(6) amendment was enacted in 1966 to ensure that a professional football league's exemption would not be jeopardized because it administered a players' pension fund.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Additionally, a professional sports league's exemption is not to be jeopardized because its primary source of revenue is the sale of television broadcasting rights to its games because the broadcasting of games increases public awareness of the sport.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] In 2013, Senator Tom Coburn introduced legislation to disallow a tax exemption for the National Football League, the Professional Golfers' Association of America, and other professional sports organizations.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Coburn estimated the tax exemption cost $100 million, but he said he could not get other members of Congress to support the legislation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A **501(c)(7) organization** is a social or recreational club that is organized for pleasure, recreation, and other nonprofitable purposes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Members must share interests and have a common goal directed toward pleasure and recreation, and the organization must provide opportunities for personal contact among members.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The organization's facilities and services must be open to its members and their guests only.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The organization must be a club of individuals, and no individual may derive profit from the organization's net earnings.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Examples include college alumni associations; college fraternities or college sororities operating chapter houses for students; country clubs; amateur sport clubs; supper clubs that provide a meeting place, library, and dining room for members; hobby clubs; and garden clubs.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A substantial amount of the 501(c)(7) organization's activities must be related to social and recreational activities for its members.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] No more than 35 percent of its gross receipts may derive from non-members, and no more than 15 percent of its gross receipts is permitted to come from use of its facilities or services by the general public.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] An organization that exceeds these limits may lose its 501(c)(7) status.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Similarly, if at least 75 percent of a group using club facilities are members of the organization, the Internal Revenue Service will assume the nonmembers are the guests of the member, and the revenue is deemed to be derived from the member.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] It is the responsibility of the organization to maintain these records.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] If the organization does not keep sufficient records to link revenue to a member, the Internal Revenue Service assumes the revenue came from a nonmember.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The organization is subject to Unrelated Business Income Tax for the revenue derived from nonmember use of its facilities and services, less allowable deductions.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] If the organization sells assets that were previously used for recreational or social purposes, the proceeds are considered related business income as long as the proceeds are reinvested in the organization.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Public use of the organization's facilities must be minimal, generally either less than $2,500 per year or less than five percent of its total gross receipts from normal and usual activities of the club.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A 501(c)(7) organization cannot have a written policy of discriminating on the basis of race, color, or religion.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Nevertheless, a 501(c)(7) organization is permitted to limit its members to a particular religion in order to further the teachings of that religion.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] An auxiliary of a 501(c)(8) fraternal benefit society that limits membership to members of a particular religion is allowed to do so as well.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Having written policies that limit its membership by ethnic origin and gender would not jeopardize the organization's tax-exempt status.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Congress justified the tax-exemption with the reasoning that the members join to provide themselves with recreational or social organization without further tax consequences, similar as if they had paid for the benefits directly.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Tax-exemption was available for organizations operated exclusively for pleasure, recreation, and other nonprofitable purposes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] In 1969, Congress passed a law stating that social and recreational clubs were permitted to engage in some unrelated business income, subject to income tax.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A **501(c)(8) organization** is a fraternal benefit society.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The society must have members of a similar calling, recreation, or profession, or members who work together to accomplish a worthy goal.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The members have associated themselves in order to help each other and to promote the common cause.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The society must have written documentation of its eligibility standards for membership, classes of membership, a process of admission, and rights and privileges of members.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The members must have a common bond, which may be based on religious beliefs, gender, occupation, ethnicity, or shared values.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The society must have a supreme governing body and subordinate lodges into which members are elected, initiated, or admitted in accordance with its laws.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The supreme governing body should be composed of delegates elected directly by members or intermediate assemblies.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The society must offer benefits to members, which may include life insurance, medical insurance, scholarships, educational programs, travel opportunities, and discount programs.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Revenue generated from providing benefits to non-members must be insubstantial to the society and may be taxable as unrelated business income.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Fraternal benefit societies trace their lineage back through mutual benefit societies, friendly societies and eventually to medieval guilds.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Many fraternal benefit societies were founded to serve the needs of immigrants and other under-served groups who shared common bonds of religion, ethnicity, gender, occupation or shared values.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Section 38 of the Payne–Aldrich Tariff Act of 1909 was the first law to provide a tax-exemption for fraternal beneficiary societies.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The tax-exemption was later codified as section 501(c)(8) with the Internal Revenue Code of 1954.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Similar to 501(c)(8) organizations, 501(c)(10) organizations are also fraternal societies, orders, or associations operating under the lodge system, but 501(c)(10) organizations do not offer life, sick, accident, or other benefits.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] 501(c)(10) organizations devote net earnings exclusively to religious, charitable, scientific, literary, educational, and fraternal purposes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A **501(c)(13)** organization is a certain type of cemetery company.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] There are two primary types of eligible cemetery companies.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A mutual cemetery company must be either "owned by and operated exclusively for the benefit of its lot owners who hold such lots for bona fide burial purposes and not for the purpose of resale" or engages in the burial of impoverished people performing similar charitable activities.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A nonprofit cemetery corporation must be incorporated solely for the purpose of the burial or the cremation of bodies and no part of its net earnings inures to the benefit of any private shareholder or individual.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Any net gain by the cemetery must be devoted to certain cemetery functions, such as the cemetery's operations, maintenance, and improvements; acquisition of cemetery property; and investment of the net gain in order to provide additional income for cemetery functions.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Net gains are not allowed to be distributed to individuals.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A perpetual care fund that is used by a profit-making cemetery to maintain cemetery properties and burial lots is not eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] On the other hand, a nonprofit organization may have a perpetual care fund without jeopardizing its exemption under Section 501(c)(13).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A cemetery that owns or operates a morgue, whether on its own grounds or elsewhere, is not eligible under 501(c)(13) because the Internal Revenue Service does not consider mortuary services necessarily incident to burial purposes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The provision of traditional burial services that directly support and maintain basic tenets and beliefs of a religion regarding burial of its members" may still be eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A cemetery that buries animals is not eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] A cemetery company wishing to be recognized under Section 501(c)(13) needs to prepare and file Form 1024 with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Charitable contributions to a 501(c)(13) organization are tax-deductible to the donor.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Payments for perpetual care of a particular lot or a particular crypt are not considered tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Payments made as part of the purchase price of a burial lot or crypt are not considered tax-deductible charitable contributions, even if a portion of the payment is for the perpetual care of the entirety of the cemetery.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Bequests or gifts to a 501(c)(13) cemetery are not deductible for federal estate tax purposes or gift tax purposes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] Historically, cemeteries were exempt from local property taxes and excise taxes in most states because states generally considered cemeteries to be performing a recognized civic service.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] The Tariff Act of 1913 provided an exemption from federal income taxes for mutual cemetery companies that were organized and operated exclusively "for the benefit of their members".
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] In 1921, Congress extended the tax-exemption to cemetery companies that are not mutual and to cemetery companies that are not operated for profit as well as any corporation solely incorporated to operate a cemetery and whose net gains do not inure to any person.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/501-c] In 1970, Congress added crematorium in the definition of cemetery for the purposes of Section 501(c)(13).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is home to the University of Michigan, the oldest university in the state.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Its economy is primarily focused on high technology, with numerous startup companies drawn to the area due to the university's robust research and development activities.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Founded in 1824 with American settlers from the East Coast, it was incorporated as a city in 1851.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] It is the principal city of its metropolitan area, and it is also included in the Detroit–Warren–Ann Arbor combined statistical area as well as the Great Lakes megalopolis.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The region was once inhabited by several Native American tribes, the most prominent being the Anishinaabe people of the Three Fires: the Odawa, Ojibwe, and Potawatomi.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The Potawatomi founded two villages in the area of what is now Ann Arbor in about 1774.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Other tribes that inhabited the area included the Wyandots and Sauk.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] These peoples established several trails that converged on present-day Ann Arbor.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The land that included Washtenaw County was ceded to the U.S. by the Odawa, Ojibwe, Potawatomi, and Wyandot in the Treaty of Detroit of 1807.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor was founded in 1824 by land speculators John Allen and Elisha Walker Rumsey.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] On May 25, 1824, the town plat was registered with Wayne County as the Village of Annarbour, the earliest known use of the town's name.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Allen and Rumsey decided to name it for their wives, both named Ann, and for the stands of bur oak in the 640 acres (260 ha) of land they purchased for $800 (equivalent to $23,000 in 2025) from the federal government at $1.25 per acre.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The local Ojibwa named the settlement *kaw-goosh-kaw-nick*, after the sound of Allen's sawmill.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor became the seat of Washtenaw County in 1827 and was incorporated as a village in 1833.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The Ann Arbor Land Company, a group of speculators, set aside 40 acres (16 ha) of undeveloped land and offered it to the state of Michigan as the site of the state capitol, but lost the bid to Lansing.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] In 1837, the property was accepted instead as the site of the University of Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Since the university's establishment in the city in 1837, the histories of the University of Michigan and Ann Arbor have been closely linked.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The town became a regional transportation hub in 1839 with the arrival of the Michigan Central Railroad, and a north–south railway connecting Ann Arbor to Toledo and other markets to the south was established in 1878.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Throughout the 1840s and the 1850s settlers continued to come to Ann Arbor.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] While the earlier settlers were primarily of British ancestry, the newer settlers also consisted of Germans, Irish, and Black people.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] In 1851, Ann Arbor was chartered as a city, though the city showed a drop in population during the Depression of 1873.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] It was not until the early 1880s that Ann Arbor again saw robust growth, with new immigrants from Greece, Italy, Russia, and Poland.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor saw increased growth in manufacturing, especially in milling.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor's Jewish community also grew after the turn of the 20th century, and its first and oldest synagogue, Beth Israel Congregation, was established in 1916.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Following a 1956 vote, the city of East Ann Arbor merged with Ann Arbor to encompass the eastern sections of the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] In 1960, Ann Arbor voters approved a $2.3 million bond issue (equivalent to $19 million in 2024) to build the current city hall, which was designed by architect Alden B.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] In 1995, the building was renamed the Guy C.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Municipal Building in honor of the longtime city administrator who championed the building's construction.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] During the 1960s and 1970s, the city gained a reputation as an important center for liberalism (liberal politics), and a locus for left-wing activism, anti-Vietnam War activism, and student activism.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The first major meetings of the national left-wing campus group Students for a Democratic Society occurred in Ann Arbor in 1960; in 1965, the city was home to the first U.S. teach-in against the Vietnam War.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] During the ensuing 15 years, many countercultural and New Left enterprises sprang up and developed large constituencies within the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] These influences washed into municipal politics during the early and mid-1970s when three members of the Human Rights Party (HRP) won city council seats on the strength of the student vote.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] During their time on the council, HRP representatives fought for measures including pioneering antidiscrimination ordinances, measures decriminalizing marijuana possession, and a rent-control ordinance.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Two religious-conservative institutions were created in Ann Arbor; the Word of God (established in 1967), a charismatic inter-denominational movement; and the Thomas More Law Center (established in 1999).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Since 1998, Ann Arbor is also the home office of the Anthroposophical Society in the United States, an organization dedicated to supporting the community of those interested in the inner path of schooling known as anthroposophy, developed by Rudolf Steiner.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] From 1967 to its closing in 1990, Ann Arbor hosted KMS Fusion, the world's first company to pursue fusion power via the inertial confinement fusion method.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] In the past several decades, Ann Arbor has grappled with the effects of sharply rising land values, gentrification, and urban sprawl stretching into outlying countryside.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] On November 4, 2003, voters approved a greenbelt plan under which the city government bought development rights on agricultural parcels of land adjacent to Ann Arbor to preserve them from sprawling development.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Since then, a vociferous local debate has hinged on how and whether to accommodate and guide development within city limits.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor consistently ranks in the "top places to live" lists published by various mainstream media outlets every year.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] In 2016, the city changed mayoral terms from two years to four.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Until 2017, City Council held annual elections in which half of the seats (one from each ward) were elected to 2-year terms.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] These elections were staggered, with each ward having one of its seats up for election in odd years and its other seat up for election in even years.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Beginning in 2018 the city council has had staggered elections to 4-year terms in even years.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] This means that half of the members (one from each ward) are elected in presidential election years, while the other half are elected in mid-term election years.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] To facilitate this change in scheduling, the 2017 election elected members to terms that lasted 3-years.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] In 2020, partly as a response to the COVID-19 pandemic, the city government opened several downtown streets to pedestrians, limiting their use by motor vehicles to emergency vehicles during summertime weekends.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] In addition to providing a large pedestrian mall, these changes allow restaurants to use more of the sidewalks and part of the street for outdoor seating.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] These changes were popular enough that in 2021 the city council extended the dates from March to November, continuing the schedule of cordoning off cars from Thursday evening until Monday morning.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor is located along the Huron River, which flows southeast through the city on its way to Lake Erie.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] It is the central core of the Ann Arbor, MI Metropolitan Statistical Area, which consists of the whole of Washtenaw County, but is also a part of the Metro Detroit Combined Statistical Area designated by the U.S.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] While it borders only Townships, the built-up nature of the sections of Pittsfield and Ypsilanti townships between Ann Arbor and the city of Ypsilanti make the two effectively a single urban area.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The landscape of Ann Arbor consists of hills and valleys, with the terrain becoming steeper near the Huron River.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The elevation ranges from about 750 feet (230 m) along the Huron River to 1,015 feet (309 m) on the city's west side, near the intersection of Maple Road and Pauline Blvd.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor is nicknamed "Tree Town", both due to its name and to the dense forestation of its parks and residential areas.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city contains more than 50,000 trees along its streets and an equal number in parks.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Into the early 2000s, the emerald ash borer has destroyed many of the city's approximately 10,500 ash trees.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city contains over 160 municipal parks ranging from small neighborhood green spots to large recreation areas such as Buhr Park.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Several large city parks and a university park border sections of the Huron River.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Fuller Recreation Area, near the University Hospital complex, contains sports fields, pedestrian and bike paths, and swimming pools.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Opened in the summer of 2014, the city-funded Ann Arbor Skatepark is a 30,000 sq ft (2,787.1 m2) skatepark located within Veterans Memorial Park.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is also home to the Washtenaw County-owned County Farm Park.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The Nichols Arboretum, owned by the University of Michigan, is a 123-acre (50 ha) arboretum that contains hundreds of plant and tree species.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] It is on the city's east side, near the university's Central Campus.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Located across the Huron River just beyond the university's North Campus is the university's Matthaei Botanical Gardens, which contains 300 acres of gardens and a large tropical conservatory.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Several other green spaces around Ann Arbor are privately owned or owned by government agencies such as Ann Arbor Public Schools.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The cityscape of Ann Arbor is heavily influenced by the University of Michigan, with 22% of downtown and 9.4% of the total land owned by the university.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The downtown Central Campus contains some of the oldest extant structures in the city—including the President's House, built in 1840—and separates the South University District from the other three downtown commercial districts.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] These other three districts, Kerrytown, State Street, and Main Street are contiguous near the northwestern corner of the university.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Major landmarks in downtown Ann Arbor include the Michigan Theater, The Diag, and Tower Plaza, a 26-story condominium building that is the city's tallest building.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Downtown is also home to several Fairy Doors and other public art installations.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Three commercial areas south of downtown include the areas near I-94 and Ann Arbor-Saline Road, Briarwood Mall, and the South Industrial area.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Other commercial areas include the Arborland/Washtenaw Avenue and Packard Road merchants on the east side, the Plymouth Road area in the northeast, and the Westgate/West Stadium areas on the west side.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Downtown contains a mix of 19th- and early-20th-century structures and modern-style buildings, as well as a farmers' market in the Kerrytown district.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city's commercial districts are composed mostly of two- to four-story structures, although downtown and the area near Briarwood Mall contain a small number of high-rise buildings.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor's residential neighborhoods contain architectural styles ranging from classic 19th- and early 20th-century designs to ranch-style houses.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Among these homes are a number of kit houses built in the early 20th century.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Contemporary-style houses are farther from the downtown district.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Surrounding the University of Michigan campus are houses and apartment complexes occupied primarily by student renters.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The 19th-century buildings and streetscape of the Old West Side neighborhood have been preserved virtually intact; in 1972, the district was listed on the National Register of Historic Places (NRHP), and it is further protected by city ordinances and a nonprofit preservation group.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor has a typically Midwestern humid continental climate (Köppen *Dfa*), which is influenced by the Great Lakes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] There are four distinct seasons: winters are cold and snowy, with average highs around 34 °F (1 °C).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Summers are warm to hot and humid, with average highs around 81 °F (27 °C) and with slightly more precipitation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Spring and autumn are transitional between the two.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The area experiences lake effect weather, primarily in the form of increased cloudiness during late fall and early winter.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The monthly daily average temperature in July is 72.6 °F (22.6 °C), while the same figure for January is 24.5 °F (−4.2 °C).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Temperatures reach or exceed 90 °F (32 °C) on 10 days, and drop to or below 0 °F (−18 °C) on 4.6 nights.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Precipitation tends to be the heaviest during the summer months, but most frequent during winter.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Snowfall, which normally occurs from November to April but occasionally starts in October, averages 58 inches (147 cm) per season.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The lowest recorded temperature was −23 °F (−31 °C) on February 11, 1885, and the highest recorded temperature was 105 °F (41 °C) on July 24, 1934.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor has seen consistent growth in population between all decennial censuses since 1860 with the exception of the 2010 census which reported almost no growth from the previous census.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] As of the 2020 U.S. census, there were 123,851 people and 49,337 households residing in the city, with a population density of 4,391.9 inhabitants per square mile (1,695.7/km2).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The racial makeup of the city including Hispanics in the racial categories was 67.6% White, 6.8% Black, 0.2% Native American, 15.7% Asian, 0.1% Native Hawaiian or Pacific Islander, 1.8% from other races, and 7.9% from two or more races.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Hispanic or Latino residents of any race made up 5.5% of the population.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor has a small population of Arab Americans, including students as well as local Lebanese and Palestinians, and a large community of Japanese nationals.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] According to the 2022 American Community Survey estimates, out of 49,337 households, 33.8% were married-couple households, 9.8% were cohabiting couple households, 26.1% had a male householder with no spouse present, and 30.4% had a female householder with no spouse present.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] 18.4% of the households had individuals under the age of 18 living in them, and 20.1% had individuals over age 65 living in them.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The average household size was 2.22 people and the average family size was 2.78 people.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The median age was 25.9; 12.2% of the population was under age 18, and 12.3% was age 65 or older.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The median household income in 2022 was $78,740 (versus the U.S. national figure of $75,149), with family households having a median income of $126,292.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The per capita income for the city was $52,276, which is higher than the U.S. national per capita income of $41,261.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Males working full-time jobs had median earnings of $86,970 compared to $61,543 for females.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Further, 3.5% of minors and 7.7% of seniors were below the poverty line.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] According to the Uniform Crime Reporting (UCR) program in 2022, Ann Arbor had 371 reported violent crimes (which include homicide, rape, robbery, and aggravated assault) and 2069 reported property crimes (which include arson, burglary, larceny-theft, and motor vehicle theft).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] With a violent crime rate of 309.5 per 100,000 people, the city's violent crime rate is lower than Michigan's rate of 461 per 100,000 people and the U.S. national rate of 380.7 per 100,000 people.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] However, Ann Arbor's property crime rate, at 1726.0 per 100,000 people, is higher than Michigan's property crime rate of 1536.8 per 100,000 people and lower than the U.S. national property crime rate of 1954.4 per 100,000 people.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The University of Michigan shapes Ann Arbor's economy significantly.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] It employs about 30,000 workers which includes about 12,000 in the medical center.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Other employers are drawn to the area by the university's research and development money, and by its graduates.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] High tech, health services and biotechnology are other major components of the city's economy; numerous medical offices, laboratories, and associated companies are located in the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Automobile manufacturers, such as General Motors and Visteon, also employ residents.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] High tech companies have located in the area since the 1930s, when International Radio Corporation introduced the first mass-produced AC/DC radio (the Kadette, in 1931) as well as the first pocket radio (the Kadette Jr., in 1933).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Firms include Arbor Networks (provider of Internet traffic engineering and security systems), Arbortext (provider of XML-based publishing software), JSTOR (the digital scholarly journal archive), Truven Health Analytics, and ProQuest, which includes UMI.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Duo Security, a cloud-based access security provider of two-factor authentication, is headquartered in Ann Arbor.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] It was formerly a unicorn and continues to be headquartered in Ann Arbor after its acquisition by Cisco Systems.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] In November 2021, semiconductor test equipment company KLA Corporation opened a new North American headquarters in Ann Arbor.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor is the home to Internet2 and the Merit Network, a not-for-profit research and education computer network.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Both are located in the South State Commons 2 building on South State Street.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is also home to a secondary office of Google's AdWords program—the company's primary revenue stream.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] As of 2022, Ann Arbor is home to more than twenty video game and XR studios of varying sizes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city plays host to a regional chapter of the International Game Developers Association (IGDA) which hosts monthly meetups, presentations, and educational events.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is the home of many research and engineering centers, including the Great Lakes Environmental Research Laboratory that is operated by NOAA and the Michigan Tech Research Institute.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Other research centers sited in the city are the United States Environmental Protection Agency's National Vehicle and Fuel Emissions Laboratory and the Toyota Technical Center.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is also home to National Sanitation Foundation International (NSF International), the nonprofit non-governmental organization that develops generally accepted standards for a variety of public health related industries and subject areas.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Non-high tech companies in Ann Arbor include Domino's Pizza, headquartered on Domino's Farms, a 271-acre (110 ha) Frank Lloyd Wright-inspired complex just northeast of the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Another Ann Arbor-based company is Zingerman's Delicatessen, which serves sandwiches and has developed businesses under a variety of brand names.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Avfuel, a global supplier of aviation fuels and services, is headquartered in Ann Arbor as is Pinkerton, a detective and private security firm.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Many cooperative enterprises were founded in the city; among those that remain are the People's Food Co-op and the Inter-Cooperative Council at the University of Michigan, a student housing cooperative founded in 1937.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] There are also three cohousing communities—Sunward, Great Oak, and Touchstone—located immediately to the west of the city limits.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Several performing arts groups and facilities are on the University of Michigan's campus, as are museums dedicated to art, archaeology, and natural history and sciences.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Founded in 1879, the University Musical Society is an independent performing arts organization that presents over 60 events each year, bringing international artists in music, dance, and theater.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Since 2001 Shakespeare in the Arb has presented one play by Shakespeare each June, in a large park near downtown.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Regional and local performing arts groups not associated with the university include the Ann Arbor Civic Theatre, the Arbor Opera Theater, the Ann Arbor Symphony Orchestra, The Ark, and Performance Network Theatre.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] State Theatre and the adjacent Michigan Theater are a movie palace and a performing arts center, respectively.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Another unique piece of artistic expression in Ann Arbor is the fairy doors.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] These small portals are examples of installation art and can be found throughout the downtown area.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The Ann Arbor Hands-On Museum, an interactive science center, is located in a renovated and expanded historic downtown fire station.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The Ann Arbor Art Center is a nonprofit that organizes art activities and exhibitions.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Aside from the Ann Arbor District Library, which maintains four branch outlets in addition to its main downtown building, and being the home to the Gerald R.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ford Presidential Library, Ann Arbor ranks first among U.S. cities in the number of booksellers and books sold per capita.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Several annual events—many of them centered on performing and visual arts—draw visitors to Ann Arbor.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] One such event is the Ann Arbor Art Fairs, a set of four concurrent juried fairs held on downtown streets.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Scheduled on Thursday through Sunday of the third week of July, the fairs draw upward of half a million visitors.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Another is the Ann Arbor Film Festival, held during the third week of March, which receives more than 2,500 submissions annually from more than 40 countries and serves as one of a handful of Academy Award–qualifying festivals in the United States.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] A person from Ann Arbor is called an "Ann Arborite", and many long-time residents call themselves "townies".
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city itself is often called "A²" ("A-squared") or "A2" ("A two") or "AA", "The Deuce" (mainly by Chicagoans), and "Tree Town".
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor is a major center for college sports, most notably at the University of Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Several well-known college sports facilities exist in the city, including Michigan Stadium, the largest American football stadium and the third-largest stadium of any kind in the world with a capacity of 107,601.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The stadium is colloquially known as "The Big House" due to its status as the largest American football stadium.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Crisler Center and Yost Ice Arena play host to the school's basketball (both men's and women's) and ice hockey teams, respectively.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Concordia University, a member of the NAIA, also fields sports teams.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] In semi-professional sports Ann Arbor is represented in the NPSL by AFC Ann Arbor, a soccer club founded in 2014 who call themselves The Mighty Oak.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] As the county seat of Washtenaw County, the Washtenaw County Trial Court (22nd Circuit Court) is located in Ann Arbor at the Washtenaw County Courthouse on Main Street.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The 15th Michigan district court, which serves only the city itself, is located within the Ann Arbor Justice Center, immediately next to city hall.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] District Court for the Eastern District of Michigan and Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit are also located in downtown Ann Arbor, at the federal building on Liberty Street.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] In the Michigan Legislature, the city is split between Districts 23, 33, 47, and 48 in the Michigan House of Representatives.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] In the Michigan Senate, Ann Arbor is covered by Districts 14 and 15.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor is within the 6th congressional district, currently represented by Debbie Dingell.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor has a council–manager form of government, with 11 voting members: the mayor and 10 city council members.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Each of the city's five wards are represented by two council members, with the mayor elected at-large during midterm years.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Half of the council members are elected in midterm years, with the other in general election years.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The mayor is the presiding officer of the city council and has the power to appoint all council committee members as well as board and commission members, with the approval of the city council.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The current mayor of Ann Arbor is Christopher Taylor, a Democrat who was elected as mayor in 2014.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Day-to-day city operations are managed by a city administrator chosen by the city council.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] While Democrats, as of 2024, hold the mayorship and all ten council seats, Ann Arbor has two major political factions.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] A major source of this local divide is differences in views on the city's growth.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Public schools are part of the Ann Arbor Public Schools (AAPS) district.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] AAPS has one of the country's leading music programs.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] For the 2021–2022 school year, 17,070 students were enrolled in the Ann Arbor Public Schools.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Notable schools include Pioneer, Huron, Skyline, Community high schools, Pathways to Success Academic Campus, and Ann Arbor Open School.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The district has a preschool center with both free and tuition-based programs for preschoolers in the district.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The University High School, a "demonstration school" with teachers drawn from the University of Michigan's education program, was part of the school system from 1924 to 1968.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor is home to several private schools, including Clonlara School, Michigan Islamic Academy, and Greenhills School, a prep school.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is also home to several charter schools such as Central Academy (Michigan) (PreK–12) of the Global Educational Excellence (GEE) charter school company.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The University of Michigan dominates the city of Ann Arbor, providing the city with its college town character.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] University buildings are located in the center of the city and the campus is directly adjacent to the State Street and South University downtown areas.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Other local colleges and universities include Concordia University Ann Arbor, a Lutheran liberal-arts institution.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] In 2000, the Ave Maria School of Law, a Roman Catholic law school established by Domino's Pizza founder Tom Monaghan, opened in northeastern Ann Arbor; the school moved to Ave Maria, Florida in 2009, and the Thomas M.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Cooley Law School acquired the former Ave Maria buildings for use as a branch campus.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Publications in the city include the *Ann Arbor Observer*, a free monthly local magazine; and *Current*, a free entertainment-focused alt-weekly.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The *Ann Arbor Business Review* covers local business in the area.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] *Car and Driver* magazine and *Automobile Magazine* are also based in Ann Arbor.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The University of Michigan is served by many student publications, including the independent *Michigan Daily* student newspaper, which reports on local, state, and regional issues in addition to campus news.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Four major AM radio stations based in or near Ann Arbor are WAAM 1600, a conservative news and talk station; WLBY 1290, a business news and talk station; WDEO 990, Catholic radio; and WTKA 1050, which is primarily a sports station.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city's FM stations include NPR affiliate WUOM 91.7; country station WWWW 102.9; and adult-alternative station WQKL 107.1.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Freeform station WCBN-FM 88.3 is a local community radio/college radio station operated by the students of the University of Michigan featuring noncommercial, eclectic music and public-affairs programming.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is also served by public and commercial radio broadcasters in Ypsilanti, the Lansing/Jackson area, Detroit, Windsor, and Toledo.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor is part of the Detroit television market.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] WPXD channel 31, the owned-and-operated Detroit outlet of the ION Television network, is licensed to the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Until its sign-off on August 31, 2017, WHTV channel 18, a MyNetworkTV-affiliated station for the Lansing market, was broadcast from a transmitter in Lyndon Township, west of Ann Arbor.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Community Television Network (CTN) is a city-provided cable television channel with production facilities open to city residents and nonprofit organizations.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Detroit and Toledo-area radio and television stations also serve Ann Arbor, and stations from Lansing and Windsor, Ontario, can be seen in parts of the area.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The University of Michigan Health System (UMHS) includes University Hospital, C.S.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Mott Children's Hospital and Women's Hospital in its core complex.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] UMHS also operates out-patient clinics and facilities throughout the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The area's other major medical centers include a large facility operated by the Department of Veterans Affairs in Ann Arbor, and Saint Joseph Mercy Hospital in nearby Superior Township.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city provides sewage disposal and water supply services, with water coming from the Huron River and groundwater sources.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] There are two water-treatment plants, one main and three outlying reservoirs, four pump stations, and two water towers.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] These facilities serve the city, which is divided into five water districts.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city's water department also operates four dams along the Huron River—Argo, Barton, Geddes, and Superior—of which Barton and Superior provide hydroelectric power.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city also offers waste management services, with Recycle Ann Arbor handling recycling service.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Other utilities are provided by private entities.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Electrical power and gas are provided by DTE Energy.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] AT&T Inc. is the primary wired telephone service provider for the area.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Cable TV service is primarily provided by Comcast.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] A plume of the industrial solvent dioxane is migrating under the city from the contaminated Gelman Sciences, Inc. property on the westside of Ann Arbor.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] As of 2021, the average measured concentration was found to be 201.19 ppb, with the maximum being 6.000 ppm.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] While the United States Environmental Protection Agency does not impose a federal limit on the level of the contaminant allowed in drinking water, the World Health Organization suggests a limit of 35 ppb.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The Gelman plume is a potential threat to one of the City of Ann Arbor's drinking water sources, the Huron River, which flows through downtown Ann Arbor.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The streets in downtown Ann Arbor conform to a grid pattern, though this pattern is less common in the surrounding areas.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Major roads branch out from the downtown district to the highways surrounding the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is belted by three freeways: Interstate 94 (I-94), which runs along the southern and western portion of the city; U.S.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Highway 23 (US 23), which primarily runs along the eastern edge of Ann Arbor; and M-14, which runs along the northern edge of the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Other nearby highways include US 12 (Michigan Avenue), M-17 (Washtenaw Avenue), and M-153 (Ford Road).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Several of the major surface arteries lead to the I-94/M-14 interchange in the west, US 23 in the east, and the city's southern areas.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The Washtenaw County Border-to-Border Trail connects Ann Arbor to Ypsilanti, mostly along the Huron River, for pedestrians, bicycles and other non-motorized transportation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The Ann Arbor Area Transportation Authority (AAATA), which brands itself as "TheRide", operates public bus services throughout the city and nearby Ypsilanti.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The AAATA operates the Blake Transit Center on Fourth Ave. in downtown Ann Arbor, and the Ypsilanti Transit Center.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] A separate zero-fare bus service operates within and between the University of Michigan campuses.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] In 2019, 36% of trips in Ann Arbor were taken by walking, biking or transit.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Since April 2012, the "AirRide" connects to Detroit Metro Airport a dozen times a day.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The Michigan Flyer, a service operated by Indian Trails, cooperates with AAATA for their AirRide and additionally offers bus service to East Lansing.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Greyhound Lines provides intercity bus service.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Megabus has direct service to Chicago, Illinois, while a bus service is provided by Amtrak Thruway for rail passengers making connections to services in East Lansing and Toledo, Ohio.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Amtrak, which provides service to the city at the Ann Arbor Train Station, operates the *Wolverine* train between Chicago and Pontiac via Detroit.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The present-day train station neighbors the city's old Michigan Central Depot, which was renovated as a restaurant in 1970.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] The Ann Arbor Railroad passes through the city and provides freight service but no passenger service.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor Municipal Airport is a small, city-run general aviation airport located just south of the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The city lies west of Seattle and is connected by an automobile ferry operated by Washington State Ferries and a passenger-only ferry operated by Kitsap Transit.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremerton spans the Port Washington Narrows and extends inland along Sinclair Inlet opposite from Port Orchard.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremerton is within the historical territory of the Suquamish people.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The land was made available for non-Native settlement by the Treaty of Point Elliott of 1855.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremerton was founded by German immigrant and real estate agent William Bremer in 1891.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] In that year, Navy Lieutenant Ambrose Barkley Wyckoff purchased approximately 190 acres (77 ha) of waterfront land on Sinclair Inlet.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] This land was owned by the Bremer family.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Navy commission determined that Point Turner, between the protected waters of the Sinclair and Dyes inlets, would be the best site in the Pacific Northwest on which to establish a shipyard.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Recognizing the large number of workers such a facility would employ, Bremer and his business partner and brother-in-law, Henry Hensel, purchased the undeveloped land near Point Turner at the inflated price of $200 per acre.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] In April 1891, Bremer arranged for the sale of 190 acres (77 ha) to the Navy at $50 per acre.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] This land became part of the initial footprint of the Puget Sound Navy Yard.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremerton was incorporated on October 15, 1901, with Alvyn Croxton serving as the city's first mayor.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Progress in the new city soon faced a major crisis, as Assistant Secretary of the Navy Charles Darling moved all repair work to the Mare Island Navy Yard in California in November 1902.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Darling cited reports from commanders that the Bremerton waterfront was rife with prostitution, opium houses and frequent strongarmed robberies of sailors.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Politics were probably also at play, as local newspapers reported that the city's incorporation left the shipyard essentially landlocked without room to expand.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] A dispute ensued between Mayor Croxton, who wanted to shutter all saloons in Bremerton, and three members of the city council, who attempted to block his efforts.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Croxton eventually won out, and the council voted to revoke all liquor licenses in June 1904.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] With the ban, Darling reestablished the navy yard as a port of call.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Saloons had begun to return to business within two years, however.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] In 1908, the city library and Union High School were established to serve the educational needs of the 2,993 residents recorded in the 1910 U.S. census.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] During World War I, submarine construction and the addition of a third drydock caused the shipyard's workforce to balloon to over 4,000 employees.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Growth due to the war effort and the 1918 annexation of the city of Manette, east of Bremerton on the Port Washington Narrows, can be seen in the 1920 census, which reported a population of 8,918.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremerton absorbed Charleston, its neighboring city to the south in 1927.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Manette was linked to Bremerton by the Manette Bridge, a 1,573-foot (479 m) bridge constructed in June 1930.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Prior to this time, the trip could only be made by ferry or a long trip around Dyes Inlet through Chico, Silverdale, and Tracyton on mostly unimproved roads.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] This wooden bridge was replaced with a concrete and steel structure in October 1949.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] It was replaced by the new Manette Bridge in 2011.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] At the shipyard, the 250-foot-tall (76 m) Hammerhead Crane No.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] One of the nation's largest, it is capable of lifting 250 tons and continues to dominate the Bremerton skyline.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] At the peak of World War II, the Bremerton area was home to an estimated 80,000 residents due to the heavy workload of shipbuilding, repair and maintenance required for the Pacific war effort.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Most of the relocation was temporary, though, and only 27,678 citizens were left in the city by 1950.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] During the 1940s, presidents Franklin D.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Roosevelt made a campaign stop at the Puget Sound Naval Shipyard on August 12, 1944, giving a national radio address in front of a backdrop of civilian workers.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] During the course of his 35-minute speech, it is believed the president suffered an angina attack, experiencing severe chest and shoulder pain.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] An electrocardiogram was immediately administered once he left the podium, but it showed nothing abnormal.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] President Truman took a two-day tour of Washington state in 1948, speaking from the balcony of the Elks Club on the morning of June 10.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Local legend has it that a man in the large Pacific Avenue crowd yelled the infamous "Give 'em hell, Harry!" line for the first time.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] This is a matter of dispute, however, as local newspapers quoted the man as having shouted "Lay it on, Harry!" Despite this, there is a bronze plaque attached to the corner of the building declaring that spot to be the place where the phrase "Give 'em hell, Harry" was first uttered.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] With the return of World War II soldiers, the need for post-secondary education became evident to officials of the Bremerton School District.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Olympic Junior College (now Olympic College), a two-year institution, opened its doors to 575 students in the fall of 1946.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Initially, it operated in the former Lincoln School building, gradually moving operations to World War II–surplus Quonset buildings at its current 16th & Chester site.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] About 100 students received associate degrees at the first commencement exercises held June 10, 1948.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] President Truman was in attendance and received the college's first honorary degree.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Operation of the college transferred from the school district to the state of Washington in 1967.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] A second high school opened in 1956, and two comprehensive high schools operated in the city until 1978.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Growth in East Bremerton necessitated the construction of another span across the Port Washington Narrows in 1958.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The $5.3 million, four-lane Warren Avenue Bridge allowed for increased traffic on State Highway 21-B (now State Route 303).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The battleship USS *Missouri*, site of the Japanese surrender treaty signing that ended World War II, was assigned to the Pacific Reserve Fleet at PSNS in 1955.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] For 30 years, she served as the city's primary tourist attraction.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Hundreds of thousands of visitors walked the "surrender deck" before the ship was recommissioned in 1985.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] She was decommissioned on March 31, 1992 (final), and her name was struck off the register on January 12, 1995.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] In 1998 "Mighty Mo" was donated to the USS *Missouri* Memorial Association and became a museum ship at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Population growth was flat, with 26,681 enumerated in the 1960 census, leading Bremerton leaders to annex the shipyard the following year in an effort to include stationed sailors in those figures.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] While the Vietnam War spawned protests and sit-ins on the Olympic College campus, the city was relatively free of civil disorder during the 1960s.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] With the 1973 selection of the Bangor Ammunition Depot 12 miles (19 km) northwest of Bremerton as the Pacific home of the new Trident submarine fleet, residential and commercial development began to move north, closer to Silverdale, and farther from the Bremerton downtown core.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Numerous failed proposals were made at redevelopment beginning in the early 1970s, including discussions of a waterfront hotel and the erection of a large canopy over the central business district.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Meanwhile, most of the city's office and retail space remained in the control of Edward Bremer, son of William Bremer and the sole remaining heir to his wealth.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremer began to neglect his properties, never increasing decades-old lease rates and failing to make necessary maintenance upgrades.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] In 1978, the Bremerton City Council passed an ordinance declaring the entire downtown a "blighted area".
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] In 1985, Safeco subsidiary Winmar Corporation developed the Kitsap Mall in Silverdale.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] With lower taxes and minimal planning regulations in the unincorporated town, Silverdale achieved virtually unfettered growth.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Penney, Montgomery Ward, Nordstrom Place Two, Woolworth and Rite Aid all closed their downtown Bremerton stores in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Upon the death of Edward Bremer in 1987, the Bremer properties were placed under the complete control of a trust held by Olympic College.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Not being in the real-estate business, the college did not actively market its holdings, and the downtown was composed almost entirely of very large empty storefronts.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] As of January 2010, many buildings remained vacant.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Despite a hard-fought battle throughout the mid-1990s by local politicians to have the decommissioned and mothballed USS *Missouri*, already in the Bremerton Navy Yard, stay in Bremerton as a museum ship and tourist attraction, Secretary of the Navy John H.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Dalton awarded the ship to the Pearl Harbor Naval Base, Hawaii, in 1998.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] It now sits near the USS *Arizona* Memorial to demonstrate where U.S. involvement in World War II started on December 7, 1941, and where it ended by the signing of the instrument of surrender by the Japanese on board the USS *Missouri,* on September 2, 1945.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Beginning with the building of a waterfront boardwalk and marina in 1992, Bremerton had begun the process of revitalizing its downtown community.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Johnson to send fighting troops in addition to the "advisors" already on the ground in Vietnam.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] In 2000, Bremerton saw the opening of the waterfront multimodal bus/ferry terminal and a hotel/conference center complex in 2004.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The high-rise Norm Dicks Government Center also opened that year, housing City Hall and other government offices.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The Waterfront Fountain Park and Naval History Museum adjacent to the Bremerton Bus/Ferry Terminal opened in 2007, and a newly expanded marina with more boat capacity was completed in 2008.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Plans to build an extension to the current boardwalk from the USS *Turner Joy* to Evergreen Park is in the litigation stage.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Even though the boardwalk extension project is fully funded, opposition to the extension by the Suquamish Tribe concerning the impact to treaty fishing rights threatens the project.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Fairfield Inn and Suites by Marriott, a 132-room hotel, opened in March 2010 on the site of the old City Hall building made obsolete by the new Norm Dicks Government Building.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Condominiums were built on the waterfront to lure more people to live and shop in the downtown area as part of the revitalization effort.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] However, construction delays and economic downturn forced the builder of the publicly funded Harborside Condominium complex, the Kitsap County Consolidated Housing Authority, to fall $40.5 million in debt.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] That debt later was taken on by Kitsap County, which hired a marketing firm to sell the remaining units at a lower-than-anticipated price.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The privately built 400-condominium complex north of the Harborside complex opened shortly before the Harborside complex and also did not sell as well as projected.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The remaining empty condos were eventually sold at auction for a lower cost.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The 2.5-acre (1.0 ha) Harborside Fountain Park opened on May 5, 2007.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Located on the waterfront just steps away from the Kitsap Conference Center, the park features five large copper-ringed fountains, wading pools, and lush landscaping.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The park will also be home to the Harborside Heritage Naval Museum.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] A tunnel underneath downtown, traversing from the ferry terminal to State Route 304 (Burwell Street), was opened to funnel traffic from the car ferry away from downtown streets.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] A new fountain park above the tunnel blends water and art, along with the bow of a ship and the conning tower of a submarine as a tribute to the workers at the Bremerton Naval Shipyard over the years.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The stations along the walk include pictures of the shipyard, workers, and shipbuilding and repair statistics.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremerton, the largest city in Kitsap County, is located directly west of Seattle across Puget Sound on the Kitsap Peninsula.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] It is bounded on the southeast and east by Sinclair Inlet and the strait of Port Orchard respectively.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The city is divided by the Port Washington Narrows, a strait spanned by two bridges that connect the eastern and western sides of the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The part of the city northeast of the narrows is referred to as East Bremerton.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The city limits extend to the southwest as far as the Mason County line and include Bremerton National Airport.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremerton is bordered to the south, across Sinclair Inlet, by the city of Port Orchard.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Census Bureau, Bremerton has a total area of 32.29 square miles (8,360 ha), of which 28.41 square miles (7,360 ha) are land and 3.88 square miles (1,000 ha) are water.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The ferry terminal and waterfront are the heart of downtown.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] As Bremerton's historic center, downtown has seen the most dramatic change over the last decade, with blighted blocks being replaced by new apartments, and older buildings being restored.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Attractions include Harborside Fountain Park, a boardwalk, and multiple naval history museums.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The Admiral Theatre, a restored 1942 Art Deco theater, is Bremerton's most prominent venue for live music and entertainment.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The district is known for breweries, coffeeshops, art galleries, and restaurants showcasing diverse cuisines.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The city is in the beginning stages of creating a public square on Fourth Street to honor local music icon Quincy Jones.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Across the water from Downtown is Manette, a neighborhood on a separate peninsula that functioned as its own town from 1891 to 1930.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] It was annexed by Bremerton in 1918, and the first Manette Bridge was completed in 1930.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Today, Manette is connected to Bremerton via the new Manette Bridge, completed in 2011.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Charleston was formerly an independent town built to house and entertain sailors, and was annexed by the city in 1927.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The neighborhood's center is Callow Avenue, a retail corridor anchored by The Charleston music venue.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Charleston is a designated center in Bremerton's comprehensive plan, and has seen recent improvements to its streetscape.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Charleston is casually defined by 11th Street to the north, Naval Avenue to the east, 1st Street to the south, and Cambrian Avenue to the west.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Between Charleston and Downtown is the Union Hill neighborhood.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Its borders are Naval Avenue to the west, 11th Street to the north, Warren Avenue to the east, and the Naval Shipyard to the south.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Union Hill is a predominantly residential neighborhood, showcasing Bremerton's most historic churches and a synagogue along Veneta Avenue.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Near Veneta and 6th is Bremerton's most architecturally notable place of worship, Our Lady Star of the Sea Catholic Church; non-native towering sequoias; and a large park.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] North of downtown's 11th Street boundary is the Evergreen neighborhood, anchored by Evergreen Park and bordered to the west by Warren Avenue.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Evergreen Park offers beach access and a boat ramp, and hosts a weekly farmer's market in the summer.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Evergreen is characterized by residential neighborhoods and water views.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] West of Evergreen and north of Union Hill and Charleston is Haddon.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Haddon's center is Lulu Haddon Park, but Bremerton High School and Olympic College's campus are main focal points as well.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Though it is an older, sleepier neighborhood traditionally more connected with the shipyard and local business, the Haddon neighborhood has recently gained notice for a few quirky businesses.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremerton has a Mediterranean climate (Köppen *Csb*), with warm dry summers and wet semi-mild winters.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Average annual precipitation is 56.93 inches (1,446.0 mm), with annual snowfall averaging 3 inches (7.62 cm).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Based on per capita income, Bremerton ranks 341st of 522 areas in the state of Washington to be ranked.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] As of the 2020 census, Bremerton had a population of 43,505.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Children under 18 made up 18.4% of the population, and 14.0% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] For every 100 females there were 111.8 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 114.6 males age 18 and over.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] 99.8% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.2% lived in rural areas.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] There were 16,809 households in Bremerton, of which 26.0% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Of all households, 35.7% were married-couple households, 25.7% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 28.8% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] About 35.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 12.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] There were 18,351 housing units, of which 8.4% were vacant.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.3% and the rental vacancy rate was 7.8%.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] As of the 2010 census, there were 37,729 people, 14,932 households, and 7,853 families residing in the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The population density was 1,328.0 inhabitants per square mile (512.7/km2).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] There were 17,273 housing units at an average density of 608.0 per square mile (234.8/km2).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The racial makeup of the city was 74.0% White, 6.7% African American, 2.0% Native American, 5.5% Asian, 1.3% Pacific Islander, 2.8% from other races, and 7.6% from two or more races.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 9.6% of the population.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] There were 14,932 households, of which 27.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 34.4% were married couples living together, 12.9% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.3% had a male householder with no wife present, and 47.4% were non-families.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] 37.3% of all households were made up of individuals, and 12.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The average household size was 2.24 and the average family size was 2.93.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The median age in the city was 31.9 years.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] 19.5% of residents were under the age of 18; 17.1% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 29% were from 25 to 44; 22.5% were from 45 to 64; and 11.9% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The gender makeup of the city was 53.1% male and 46.9% female.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremerton is divided among three state legislative districts in Kitsap County, the 23rd legislative district to the north, 35th legislative district in the center and 26th legislative district to the south.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Before redistricting in 2012, the line separating the first and sixth Congressional districts ran through East Bremerton.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] As a result of the 2012 redistricting, all of Bremerton now lies within the sixth Congressional district.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The district is represented by Emily Randall, who was first elected to that position in 2024.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Prior to Randall, Derek Kilmer served as sixth district Representative from 2012 to 2025.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Greg Wheeler was elected mayor in 2017 and re-elected in 2021.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Incorporated as a first-class city, Bremerton has been governed by a nonpartisan strong mayor and seven-member city council since 1985.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Each member is elected from one of seven districts who in turn elect one member as President.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The current form of government was established by a 1983 charter that eliminated a decades-old city commission composed of a mayor, public works commissioner and finance commissioner.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Each member of the Kitsap County Board of Commissioners represents a portion of the city of Bremerton.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] This arrangement was an attempt to balance Bremerton's commercial influence with the remainder of the county, though most of its sales tax base has since relocated to unincorporated areas.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremerton politics can vary in intensity, with some city council positions regularly unopposed and others having as many as four candidates in the 2005 primary election, and seven candidates in the 2021 election.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] As with most cities in the region, Bremerton precincts have historically been more favorable for Democratic candidates in state and federal elections, contrasting with more conservative-leaning voters in rural areas of the county.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremerton is home to the longest-running Armed Forces Day Parade in the United States west of the Mississippi River.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] All branches of the military, police and firefighters, youth organizations, dignitaries, commercial businesses, car clubs, Bremerton High School's marching band, and more participate in the Downtown for an afternoon celebration on the third Saturday of May.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Annual attendance is between 22,000 to 40,000 people.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The Blackberry Festival is held annually during Labor Day weekend on the waterfront boardwalk to celebrate blackberries.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The three-day event include food stalls, arts and crafts, live entertainment, foot races, and a bicycle race.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremerton National Airport sponsors the annual Blackberry Festival Fly-In, which is accessed through Kitsap Transit's shuttle buses.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Public schools are operated by the Bremerton School District, Central Kitsap School District, and South Kitsap School District.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] College level education is offered by Olympic College.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Christ the King Lutheran School is a Pre-K-8 grade school of the Wisconsin Evangelical Lutheran Synod in Bremerton.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremerton was home to the Kitsap BlueJackets, a summer collegiate baseball team that played in the West Coast League from 2005 to 2016.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The BlueJackets played at Gene Lobe Field, located on the county fairgrounds, and had low attendance due to their lack of winning seasons.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The team planned to move to a new league, but instead moved to Port Angeles to become the Port Angeles Lefties in 2017.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The city previously had another minor league baseball team, the Bremerton Bluejackets of the Western International League, in the late 1940s.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The Kitsap Pumas, a semi-professional soccer team in the USL Premier Development League (PDL), were based in Bremerton from 2009 to 2018.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The team won the league's national championship in 2011 and finished as runners-up in 2014; they also participated in the U.S.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Open Cup and defeated professional teams in the upper leagues of the national pyramid.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] After moving to the National Premier Soccer League for their final two seasons, the Pumas (then renamed Kitsap Soccer Club) folded in 2018 due to attendance figures declining significantly since their early years.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Several junior ice hockey teams have played at the Bremerton Ice Center, which operated the West Sound Warriors from 2003 to 2019.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The team, originally named the Puget Sound Tomahawks, were relocated from Tacoma in 2003; they played in the Northern Pacific Hockey League until it disbanded in 2016, then moved to the United States Premier Hockey League.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The Warriors name was transferred to the relocated Vancouver Rangers of the Western States Hockey League in 2017, but the team suspended operations at the end of their first season.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] A new team, the West Sound Admirals of the Western States Hockey League, played the following season in Bremerton but disbanded before the end of the 2019–20 season.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The Bremerton Sockeyes of the United States Premier Hockey League formed in 2024 and play at the Bremerton Ice Center.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The city was home to a semi-professional basketball team, named the Kitsap Admirals, that played in various leagues from 2012 to 2023.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] They were founded as an expansion team in the American Basketball Association and later played as an independent franchise before they moved to the North American Basketball League.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] In 2005, the International Speedway Corporation proposed the construction of a NASCAR racetrack near Bremerton National Airport after a previous plan for Marysville was shelved.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The planned 1.2-mile (1.9 km) racetrack would seat 80,000 spectators and cover 950 acres (380 ha); half of the projected $345 million cost would be financed by the state government through bonds.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Local residents and elected officials both protested the plan, which was eventually abandoned in 2007 after a lack of support from the state legislature.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] A NASCAR Grand National Series race had previously been held at the airport in April 1957 as part of Seafair, but only attracted 14 drivers and 2,500 spectators—far short of the expected turnout.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The Bremerton Transportation Center is a major intermodal hub for Kitsap County that opened in 2000 and is served by ferries and buses.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The Washington State Ferries system, the largest of its kind in the United States, operates the Seattle–Bremerton ferry with large vessels capable of carrying up to 1,500 passengers and 144 vehicles.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] In 2024, the Seattle–Bremerton route carried 990,435 total passengers and 362,529 vehicles.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The facility is also the main hub for Kitsap Transit, the provider of public transit in Bremerton and Kitsap County.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The agency operates passenger-only Kitsap Fast Ferries to Seattle as well as local foot ferries to Port Orchard and Annapolis.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Kitsap Transit's buses serve the terminal as well as other areas of the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The state ferry takes approximately an hour to complete its Seattle–Bremerton journey, while the fast ferries take 28 minutes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The main highway through Bremerton and surrounding areas is State Route 3, which connects the Kitsap Peninsula to Shelton and the Hood Canal Bridge.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] In western Bremerton, State Route 3 is a freeway that bypasses the city center; other state highways, including State Route 303 and State Route 304, provide connections within the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Two bridges over the Port Washington Narrows connect Downtown Bremerton to nearby neighborhoods: the Warren Avenue Bridge, which carries State Route 303 and opened in 1958; and the Manette Bridge, which opened in 1929 and was replaced by a new structure in 2011.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremerton National Airport is located in southwestern Bremerton and is operated by the Port of Bremerton primarily for general aviation and corporate jets.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] It has a 6,000-foot (1,800 m) runway that is capable of landing some jet airliners, over 162 hangars, and an industrial park with warehouses.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The airport was built in 1936 for civilian use and was later used by the United States Navy for operations during World War II and most of the late 20th century.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] The Port of Bremerton was deeded the airport in 1963 and has proposed an extension of the runway to accommodate regular commercial service.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/bremerton-washington] Bremerton National was among a shortlist of candidates in the state government's 2021 study into alternative airports to relieve capacity issues at Seattle–Tacoma International Airport, the largest commercial airport in the region.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] **consortiums** or **consortia**) is an association of two or more individuals, companies, organizations, or governments (or any combination of these entities) with the objective of participating in a common activity or pooling their resources for achieving a common goal.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Consortia are generally nonprofit with a goal to help its members improve their competitiveness in the specific field.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Consortiums among universities are established to share research laboratories and equipment facilities, exchange faculty and students, provide programs abroad, and form specialized research centers and admissions offices.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Generally, it includes a corporate identity, voluntary membership of institutions, its own staff and budgetary autonomy.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] This type of consortium aims to facilitate the educational process and research by more effectively allocating and conserving limited resources of money, staff, and facilities, identifying specialized areas of teaching and research in which cooperative deals would be alluring.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Two types of high education consortia are generally realized, the "association" and the "center".
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The "association" refers to colleges and universities of similar nature and purpose; the "center" type brings together dissimilar institutions: smaller colleges around a large university.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The Big Ten Academic Alliance in the Midwest and Mid-Atlantic U.S., Claremont Colleges consortium in Southern California, Five College Consortium in Massachusetts, and Consórcio Nacional Honda are among the oldest and most successful higher education consortia in the world.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The Big Ten Academic Alliance, formerly known as the Committee on Institutional Cooperation, includes the members of the Big Ten athletic conference.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The participants in Five Colleges, Inc. are: Amherst College, Hampshire College, Mount Holyoke College, Smith College, and the University of Massachusetts Amherst.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Another example of a successful consortium is the Five Colleges of Ohio of Ohio: Oberlin College, Ohio Wesleyan University, Kenyon College, College of Wooster and Denison University.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The aforementioned Claremont Consortium (known as the Claremont Colleges) consists of Pomona College, Claremont Graduate University, Scripps College, Claremont McKenna College, Harvey Mudd College, Pitzer College, and Keck Graduate Institute.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] These consortia have pooled the resources of their member colleges and the universities to share human and material assets as well as to link academic and administrative resources.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] An example of a non-profit consortium is the Appalachian College Association (ACA) located in Richmond, Kentucky.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The association consists of 35 private liberal arts colleges and universities spread across the central Appalachian mountains in Kentucky, North Carolina, Tennessee, Virginia, and West Virginia.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Collectively these higher education institutions serve approximately 42,500 students.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Six research universities in the region (University of Kentucky, University of North Carolina, University of Tennessee, West Virginia University, University of Virginia, and Virginia Tech) are affiliated with the ACA.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] These institutions assist the ACA in reviewing grant and fellowship applications, conducting workshops, and providing technical assistance.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The ACA works to serve higher education in the rural regions of these five states.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] An example of a for-profit consortium is a group of banks that collaborate to make a loan—also known as a syndicate.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] This type of loan is more commonly known as a syndicated loan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] In England, it is common for a consortium to buy out financially struggling football clubs in order to keep them out of liquidation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Alyeska Pipeline Service Company, the company that built the Trans-Alaska Pipeline System in the 1970s, initially was a consortium of BP, ARCO, ConocoPhillips, Exxon, Mobil, Unocal, and Koch Alaska Pipeline Company.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Airbus Industries was formed in 1970 as a consortium of aerospace manufacturers.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The retention of production and engineering assets by the partner companies in effect made Airbus Industries a sales and marketing company.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] This arrangement led to inefficiencies due to the inherent conflicts of interest that the four partner companies faced; they were both shareholders of, and subcontractors to, the consortium.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The companies collaborated on development of the Airbus range, but guarded the financial details of their own production activities and sought to maximize the transfer prices of their sub-assemblies.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] In 2001, EADS (created by the merger of French, German and Spanish Airbus partner companies) and BAE Systems (the British partner company) transferred their Airbus production assets to a new company, Airbus SAS.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] In return, they got 80% and 20% shares respectively.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] For example, the GENIVI Alliance, now called COVESA, is a not-for-profit consortium between different car makers in order to ease building an In-Vehicle Infotainment system.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Another example is the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), which is a consortium that standardizes web technologies like HTML, XML and CSS.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The Institute for Food Safety and Health is a consortium consisting of the Illinois Institute of Technology, the Food and Drug Administration's Center for Food Safety and Applied Nutrition, and members of the food industry.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Some of the work done at the institute includes, "assessment and validation of new and novel food safety and preservation technologies, processing and packaging systems, microbiological and chemical methods, health promoting food components, and risk management strategies".
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] In this association its members contribute by paying equal amount installments (usually monthly or weekly) towards a common fund.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] On every installment the common fund reaches the goal value and someone is awarded this sum and from this point forward this person own the association the remaining amount, just as in a loan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] This process repeats until every member is awarded the entire sum.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] These informal associations are specially popular among immigrants since they are a cheaper alternative to traditional financing and usually require no formal papers, credit history or even a bank account.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Outside the United States, these savings clubs can be formal and have proper legislation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] In some countries, like Brazil, *consórcios* are an integral part of the traditional banking system, where there are clubs for purchasing real estate and cars, and even for plastic surgery costs.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Over seven million people have engaged in these formal savings associations over the past years, adding to over U$10 billion in credit.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Since these clubs have up to thousands of members, products purchased are awarded through lottery and bidding processes and the common fund administrators charge a fixed fee in order to take responsibility and guarantee the integrity of the process.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] In France, the consortium, considered a sub-type of joint venture, has important theoretical and practical significance.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The French legal system does not provide a definition and does not explicitly use the concept of a joint venture or consortium (*groupements momentanés d’entreprises*).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The consortium agreement in France is a purely contractual cooperative contract that does not entail the creation of a third party.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The consortium has no legal personality or legal capacity.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The contract is concluded between two or more natural or legal persons who undertake to carry out certain works in order to implement a joint project which consortium members would not be able to carry out themselves.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The consortium agreement is not explicitly regulated by the French legislator, but it is admissible in the light of the principle of freedom of contract interpreted from articles 6 and 1134 of the French Civil Code.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Neither consortium nor joint venture have a legal definition in U.K. law.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The second term is usually used to describe various types of agreements where two or more parties cooperate in conducting business activities.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] This manifests e.g. in the joint distribution of profit, sharing cash, assets, knowledge or abilities.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] A consortium agreement governed by the general law of contract, similar to an ordinary partnership agreement, does not create a separate entity.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] In Germany the view prevails that the consortium is a type of internal civil law partnership (§ 705–740 of the BGB).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] In external relations, consortium members may decide on joint and several liability regulated by § 421 BGB, while internally there is sometimes a release from this liability.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Joint ventures often include credit syndicates (Kreditkonsortien), securities issuing consortia, including mainly shares (*Emissionskonsortien*), construction consortia (*Baukonsortien*) also referred to as investment (*Investitionskonsortien*) and profit pools (*Ergebnispools*).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Sometimes, special purpose partnerships established to jointly use construction facilities (*Planungsgesellschaften*) are listed in one category with the consortium and the pool.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] Cooperation agreements concluded under German law are not of a uniform legal nature.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] There is a great wealth of legal forms of cooperation that could be cautiously qualified as consortium agreements.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] This is in particular a civil law partnership in its internal and occasional variants (*Gelegenheitsgesellschaft*), as well as a partnership of building contractors (*ARGE*) and a structure simply referred to as the "consortium".
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] In Italy, a consortium is governed by the Italian Civil Code.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The Civil Code (also known as the “Civil Code of 1942”) in Italy is a body of civil law provisions and general procedural law rules and criminal rules.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] The code currently in force was issued with the Royal Decree of 16 March 1942, no.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/consortium] In the Polish legal system, the legal nature of the consortium agreement is disputed.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Although the two cities have separate services and addresses, Farmington and Farmington Hills are often thought of as the same community.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] These two cities combined were part of Farmington Township in the time of the Northwest Territory.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The community has several historical sites, including the Governor Warner Mansion.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Both cities are served by Farmington Public Schools and the Farmington Community Library.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Farmington Hills is the home of the Zekelman Holocaust Center, the only Holocaust memorial in the State of Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The Zekelman Holocaust Center was originally located in neighboring West Bloomfield Township, but has since expanded and moved to its current facility.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 33.31 square miles (86.27 km2), of which 33.28 square miles (86.19 km2) is land and 0.03 square miles (0.08 km2) is water.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Farmington Hills is bordered by West Bloomfield to the north, Franklin and Southfield to the east, Livonia to the south, and Novi to the west.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The first white settler in what became Farmington Township was a Quaker from Farmington, New York, named Arthur Power.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] He purchased land in 1823 and returned in 1824 with a group of families and associates to clear the land.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The settlement became known as **Quakertown**.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] A post office was established in February 1826 with the name of Farmington.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The original post office is still standing today and is a designated historic site.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The township of Farmington was organized in 1827, and the settlement was incorporated as the village of Farmington in the winter of 1866–67.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] A fire on October 9, 1872, destroyed many buildings in the village center.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Farmington was incorporated as a city in 1926.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] A small settlement was also developed in **Clarenceville**, in the extreme southeast corner of the township on the boundary with Livonia in Wayne County.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Stephen Jennings built a tavern and a general store (now the Botsford Inn) to accommodate travelers on the plank road between Detroit and Howell.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The name remains in the Clarenceville School District.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Even though the school buildings for Clarenceville are in Livonia in Wayne County, the school district serves a portion of Farmington Hills.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] In 1839, a post office named **East Farmington** was opened, but it closed in 1842.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] In 1847, a post office named **North Farmington** was established a mile south of the township line as Wolcott's Corners.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] After the death of postmaster Chauncey D.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Walcott in 1865, the office moved to the township line in the northeast quarter of section 4 (near the intersection of 14 Mile Road and Farmington Road).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The post office functioned until September 1902.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Before the remainder of Farmington Township was incorporated as the city of Farmington Hills, there were two other incorporated entities within its boundaries.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The first began as a subdivision named **Quaker Valley Farms** that was incorporated as the village of Quakertown in 1959.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The other was **Wood Creek Farms**, developed in 1937 as a subdivision by George Wellington of Franklin, who named it after a New England estate.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] It was incorporated as a village in 1957.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The villages, together with the remainder of Farmington Township, were incorporated into the City of Farmington Hills in 1973.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The City grew rapidly throughout the mid-20th century.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] A community called **Quakertown North** was recognized in the 1970 United States census, with a population of 7,101 recorded.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] It was located north of the former municipality of Quakertown.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The land area was 1.6 square miles and a housing unit count of 1,803.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The area, along with neighboring communities merged, to the newly created city of Farmington Hills in 1973.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The ZIP code serving the area was 48331.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Farmington Hills is home to the headquarters of numerous major companies, including Gale, Mango Languages, 5-Hour Energy, and The Sharper Image, as well as the United States headquarters of Bosch, Mercedes-Benz Financial Services, and TD Auto Finance.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The city was also previously home to the headquarters of Compuware, White Motor Company, A&W Restaurants, and Michigan National Bank.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Nissan's North American technical center is located in Farmington Hills.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The Nissan technical center handled project engineering of vehicle bodies used in North America and Latin America.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] It also has a small laboratory, where as of 2012, research is being conducted with hydrogen fuel cells.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The company planned to add electrical battery and recharging of electrical vehicle research to the laboratory.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] As of January 2012 the technical center had 800 full-time employees.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] At that time Nissan planned to hire 150 more engineers to work in the technical center.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The technical center opened in November 1991 at a cost of $80 million.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] In 2005, Nissan added a $14 million design studio at their Farmington Hills campus, and the Nissan AZEAL was the first car to be designed there.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Hitachi Automotive Systems Americas, Inc. maintains an office in Farmington Hills, as does Panasonic Automotive Systems.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Lordstown Motors operates a research and development center in Farmington Hills.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Farmington Hills operates under the council-manager form of government.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] It is governed by a 7-member city council, consisting of a mayor elected to two-year terms, and six councilmembers elected to staggered four-year terms.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Councilmembers serve at-large, and are elected in a nonpartisan capacity in odd-numbered years.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Mayors are limited to two consecutive terms, while other councilmembers are not subject to term limits.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The council elects one of its members to serve as mayor pro tempore.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The city council appoints a city manager, who manages the day-to-day operations of the city; a clerk who oversees elections and maintains city codes, ordinances, resolutions and other legal documents; and a city attorney who acts as a legal advisor and representative for all City matters.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The Mayor's Youth Council is an active teen committee/council who work under the city to help address teen problems and issues.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] This council helped to build the Riley Skate Park (the largest skate park in the Midwest), and sends delegates to the National League of Cities (NLC) conferences, has articles published in the local newspaper, helps run citywide events, organizes battle of the bands, and hosts their own talk show.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The Commission for Children, Youth and Families, operated in partnership with neighboring Farmington, is dedicated to creating a welcoming community for individuals of all ages and backgrounds.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] In 2006, a public meeting was held in Farmington Hills to discuss the possible merger with Farmington as a money-saving venture and also as a way to keep the two communities vibrant.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Farmington and Farmington Hills already share several services, such as a school district, a library system, and a district court.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] However, both cities utilize their own fire departments, and Farmington has a public safety department rather than a police department.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] According to a 2015 estimate, the median income for a household in the city was $93,274, and the median income for a family was $198,136.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Males had a median income of $61,757 versus $39,540 for females.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The per capita income for the city was $36,134.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Farmington Hills is well known for its luxury estates, its rolling hills, and is also listed on Forbes as one of the most prosperous suburbs in the US, with a household net worth of $725,120.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] About 2.4% of families and 4.1% of the population were below the poverty line, including 3.2% of those under age 18 and 7.6% of those age 65 or over.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] As of the 2020 census, Farmington Hills had a population of 83,986 and a population density of 2,396.0 inhabitants per square mile (925.1/km2).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] 18.3% of residents were under the age of 18 and 20.1% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] For every 100 females there were 93.7 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 91.9 males age 18 and over.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] There were 35,352 households in Farmington Hills, of which 25.0% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Of all households, 49.6% were married-couple households, 18.8% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 27.2% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] About 31.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] There were 37,382 housing units, of which 5.4% were vacant.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.0% and the rental vacancy rate was 8.2%.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] 100.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] As of the census of 2010, there were 79,740 people, 33,559 households, and 21,412 families residing in the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The population density was 2,396.0 inhabitants per square mile (925.1/km2).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] There were 36,178 housing units at an average density of 1,087.1 per square mile (419.7/km2).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The racial makeup of the city was 69.7% White, 17.4% African American, 0.2% Native American, 10.1% Asian, 0.4% from other races, and 2.2% from two or more races.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Together, individuals of Hispanic or Latino identification comprised 1.9% of the population.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] There were 33,559 households, of which 29.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 50.7% were married couples living together, 9.9% had a female householder with no husband present, 3.2% had a male householder with no wife present, and 36.2% were non-families.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] 31.5% of all households were made up of individuals, and 12% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The average household size was 2.36 and the average family size was 3.00.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The median age in the city was 42.1 years.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] 21.5% of residents were under the age of 18; 7.1% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 25.2% were from 25 to 44; 30.2% were from 45 to 64; and 15.9% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The gender makeup of the city was 47.1% male and 52.9% female.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] In April 2013, Farmington Hills had the fourth largest Japanese national population in the state of Michigan, at 589.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] As of the census of 2000, there were 82,111 people, 33,559 households, and 21,813 families residing in the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The population density was 2,466.4 inhabitants per square mile (952.3/km2).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] There were 34,858 housing units at an average density of 1,047.0 per square mile (404.2/km2).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The racial makeup of the city was 82.95% White, 6.94% African American, 0.17% Native American, 7.54% Asian, 0.02% Pacific Islander, 0.46% from other races, and 1.93% from two or more races.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 1.47% of the population.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] 12.6% were of German, 9.1% Polish, 8.3% Irish, 7.1% English and 5.5% Italian ancestry according to Census 2000.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] There were 33,559 households, out of which 29.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 56.0% were married couples living together, 6.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 35.0% were non-families.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] 29.6% of all households were made up of individuals, and 10.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The average household size was 2.41 and the average family size was 3.04.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] In the city, the population was spread out, with 23.1% under the age of 18, 6.7% from 18 to 24, 31.3% from 25 to 44, 24.6% from 45 to 64, and 14.4% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] For every 100 females, there were 93.8 males.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 90.2 males.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Almost all of Farmington Hills is located in the Farmington Public Schools district.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The district includes eight elementary schools, three middle schools, and one K-8 lottery school, of which all but one are located in Farmington Hills.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] North Farmington High School, a large traditional high school, and Farmington Central High School, a smaller alternative high school, are located in Farmington Hills, and Farmington High School in neighboring Farmington also serves portions of Farmington Hills.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Harrison High School also operated in the city from 1970 until its closure in 2019, after which it was repurposed as a community center, named The Hawk.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Small portions of the city are within the Clarenceville and Walled Lake Consolidated school districts.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The city is also home to Oakland Early College, an early college high school administered by the West Bloomfield School District.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The area includes several private schools, including two parochial Catholic schools, Our Lady of Sorrows and St.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Fabian, run by the Archdiocese of Detroit.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Fabian is in Farmington Hills, and Our Lady of Sorrows School is in Farmington.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Farmington Hills also includes an all-girls Catholic high school, Mercy High School, one Lutheran school, Concordia Lutheran School/St.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Paul's Lutheran Preschool, and Hillel Day School, a non-denominational Jewish day school.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The Orchard Ridge campus of Oakland Community College is located in Farmington Hills, as is the Michigan School of Psychology.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Farmington Hills was also the location for the fictitious University of Farmington, created by the U.S.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Immigration and Customs Enforcement's Homeland Security Investigations (HSI) as part of a sting operation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The major thoroughfares in the city are M-5, Orchard Lake Road, 12 Mile Road, 8 Mile Road, Northwestern Highway, I-696, and I-275.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] The city contains several freeway interchanges connecting local roads to the two interstates.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/farmington-hills-michigan] Public transit services are provided by SMART.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] A **machine tool** is a machine for handling or machining metal or other rigid materials, usually by cutting, boring, grinding, shearing, or other forms of deformations.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Machine tools employ some sort of tool that does the cutting or shaping.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] All machine tools have some means of constraining the workpiece and provide a guided movement of the parts of the machine.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Thus, the relative movement between the workpiece and the cutting tool (which is called the **toolpath**) is controlled or constrained by the machine to at least some extent, rather than being entirely "offhand" or "freehand".
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] It is a power-driven metal cutting machine which assists in managing the needed relative motion between cutting tool and the job that changes the size and shape of the job material.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] The precise definition of the term *machine tool* varies among users.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] While all machine tools are "machines that help people to make things", not all factory machines are machine tools.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Today machine tools are typically powered other than by the human muscle (e.g., electrically, hydraulically, or via line shaft), used to make manufactured parts (components) in various ways that include cutting or certain other kinds of deformation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] With their inherent precision, machine tools enabled the economical production of interchangeable parts.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] In this view of the definition, the term, arising at a time when all tools up till then had been hand tools, simply provided a label for "tools that were machines instead of hand tools".
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] This lathe "produced screw threads out of wood and employed a true compound slide rest".
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] National Bureau of Economic Research (NBER) referenced the definition of a machine tool as "any machine operating by other than hand power which employs a tool to work on metal".
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] The narrowest colloquial sense of the term reserves it only for machines that perform metal cutting—in other words, the many kinds of conventional machining and grinding.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] These processes are a type of deformation that produces swarf.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] However, economists use a slightly broader sense that also includes metal deformation of other types that squeeze the metal into shape without cutting off swarf, such as rolling, stamping with dies, shearing, swaging, riveting, and others.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Thus presses are usually included in the economic definition of machine tools.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Many reports on machine tool export and import and similar economic topics use this broader definition.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] The colloquial sense implying conventional metal cutting is also growing obsolete because of changing technology over the decades.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] In addition, some of the newly developed additive manufacturing processes, which are not about cutting away material but rather about adding it, are done by machines that are likely to end up labeled, in some cases, as machine tools.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] In fact, machine tool builders are already developing machines that include both subtractive and additive manufacturing in one work envelope, and retrofits of existing machines are underway.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] In modern precision engineering, the accuracy of machine tool components is often maintained through the use of a Hirth joint.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] This coupling is the industry standard for high-accuracy positioning in components such as CNC rotary tables and tool turrets.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Its straight-tooth geometry provides maximum static stiffness and positional repeatability, ensuring that the machine maintains micron-level alignment while resisting heavy cutting forces during the machining process.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Forerunners of machine tools included bow drills and potter's wheels, which had existed in ancient Egypt prior to 2500 BC, and lathes, known to have existed in multiple regions of Europe since at least 1000 to 500 BC.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] But it was not until the later Middle Ages and the Age of Enlightenment that the modern concept of a machine tool—a class of machines used as tools in the making of metal parts, and incorporating machine-guided toolpath—began to evolve.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Clockmakers of the Middle Ages and renaissance men such as Leonardo da Vinci helped expand humans' technological milieu toward the preconditions for industrial machine tools.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] During the 18th and 19th centuries, and even in many cases in the 20th, the builders of machine tools tended to be the same people who would then use them to produce the end products (manufactured goods).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] However, from these roots also evolved an industry of machine tool builders as we define them today, meaning people who specialize in building machine tools for sale to others.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Historians of machine tools often focus on a handful of major industries that most spurred machine tool development.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Others could be included in this list as well, but they tend to be connected with the root causes already listed.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Machine tools filled a need created by textile machinery during the Industrial Revolution in England in the middle to late 1700s.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Until that time, machinery was made mostly from wood, often including gearing and shafts.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] The increase in mechanization required more metal parts, which were usually made of cast iron or wrought iron.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Cast iron could be cast in molds for larger parts, such as engine cylinders and gears, but was difficult to work with a file and could not be hammered.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Red hot wrought iron could be hammered into shapes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Room temperature wrought iron was worked with a file and chisel and could be made into gears and other complex parts; however, hand working lacked precision and was a slow and expensive process.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] James Watt was unable to have an accurately bored cylinder for his first steam engine, trying for several years until John Wilkinson invented a suitable boring machine in 1774, boring Boulton & Watt's first commercial engine in 1776.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] The advance in the accuracy of machine tools can be traced to Henry Maudslay and refined by Joseph Whitworth.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] The process by which the master plane gages were produced dates back to antiquity but was refined to an unprecedented degree in the Maudslay shop.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] The process begins with three square plates each given an identification (ex., 1,2 and 3).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] The first step is to rub plates 1 and 2 together with a marking medium (called bluing today) revealing the high spots which would be removed by hand scraping with a steel scraper, until no irregularities were visible.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] This would not produce true plane surfaces but a "ball and socket" concave-concave and convex-convex fit, as this mechanical fit, like two perfect planes, can slide over each other and reveal no high spots.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] The rubbing and marking are repeated after rotating 2 relative to 1 by 90 degrees to eliminate concave-convex "potato-chip" curvature.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Next, plate number 3 is compared and scraped to conform to plate number 1 in the same two trials.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] In this manner plates number 2 and 3 would be identical.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Next plates number 2 and 3 would be checked against each other to determine what condition existed, either both plates were "balls" or "sockets" or "chips" or a combination.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] These would then be scraped until no high spots existed and then compared to plate number 1.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Repeating this process of comparing and scraping the three plates could produce plane surfaces accurate to within millionths of an inch (the thickness of the marking medium).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] The traditional method of producing the surface gages used an abrasive powder rubbed between the plates to remove the high spots, but it was Whitworth who contributed the refinement of replacing the grinding with hand scraping.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Sometime after 1825, Whitworth went to work for Maudslay and it was there that Whitworth perfected the hand scraping of master surface plane gages.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] With the creation of master plane gages of such high accuracy, all critical components of machine tools (i.e., guiding surfaces such as machine ways) could then be compared against them and scraped to the desired accuracy.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] The first machine tools offered for sale (i.e., commercially available) were constructed by Matthew Murray in England around 1800.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Others, such as Henry Maudslay, James Nasmyth, and Joseph Whitworth, soon followed the path of expanding their entrepreneurship from manufactured end products and millwright work into the realm of building machine tools for sale.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Important early machine tools included the slide rest lathe, screw-cutting lathe, turret lathe, milling machine, pattern tracing lathe, shaper, and metal planer, which were all in use before 1840.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] With these machine tools the decades-old objective of producing interchangeable parts was finally realized.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] An important early example of something now taken for granted was the standardization of screw fasteners such as nuts and bolts.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Before about the beginning of the 19th century, these were used in pairs, and even screws of the same machine were generally not interchangeable.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Methods were developed to cut screw thread to a greater precision than that of the feed screw in the lathe being used.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] This led to the bar length standards of the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] American production of machine tools was a critical factor in the Allies' victory in World War II.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Production of machine tools tripled in the United States in the war.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] No war was more industrialized than World War II, and it has been written that the war was won as much by machine shops as by machine guns.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] The production of machine tools is concentrated in about 10 countries worldwide: China, Japan, Germany, Italy, South Korea, Taiwan, Switzerland, US, Austria, Spain and a few others.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Machine tool innovation continues in several public and private research centers worldwide.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Machine tools can be powered from a variety of sources.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Human and animal power (via cranks, treadles, treadmills, or treadwheels) were used in the past, as was water power (via water wheel); however, following the development of high-pressure steam engines in the mid 19th century, factories increasingly used steam power.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Factories also used hydraulic and pneumatic power.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Many small workshops continued to use water, human and animal power until electrification after 1900.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Today most machine tools are powered by electricity; hydraulic and pneumatic power are sometimes used, but this is uncommon.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Machine tools can be operated manually, or under automatic control.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Early machines used flywheels to stabilize their motion and had complex systems of gears and levers to control the machine and the piece being worked on.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Soon after World War II, the numerical control (NC) machine was developed.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] NC machines used a series of numbers punched on paper tape or punched cards to control their motion.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] In the 1960s, computers were added to give even more flexibility to the process.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Such machines became known as computerized numerical control (CNC) machines.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] NC and CNC machines could precisely repeat sequences over and over, and could produce much more complex pieces than even the most skilled tool operators.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Before long, the machines could automatically change the specific cutting and shaping tools that were being used.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] For example, a drill machine might contain a magazine with a variety of drill bits for producing holes of various sizes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Previously, either machine operators would usually have to manually change the bit or move the work piece to another station to perform these different operations.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] The next logical step was to combine several different machine tools together, all under computer control.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] These are known as machining centers, and have dramatically changed the way parts are made.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] When fabricating or shaping parts, several techniques are used to remove unwanted metal.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Other techniques are used to *add* desired material.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] Devices that fabricate components by selective *addition* of material are called rapid prototyping machines.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] The worldwide market for machine tools was approximately $81 billion in production in 2014 according to a survey by market research firm Gardner Research.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] The largest producer of machine tools was China with $23.8 billion of production followed by Germany and Japan at neck and neck with $12.9 billion and $12.88 billion respectively.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/machine-tool] South Korea and Italy rounded out the top 5 producers with revenue of $5.6 billion and $5 billion respectively.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan consists of two peninsulas: the heavily forested Upper Peninsula (commonly called "the U.P."), which juts eastward from northern Wisconsin, and the more populated Lower Peninsula, stretching north from Ohio and Indiana.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The peninsulas are separated by the Straits of Mackinac, which connects Lake Michigan and Lake Huron, and are linked by the 5-mile-long Mackinac Bridge along Interstate 75.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Bordering four of the five Great Lakes and Lake St.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Clair, Michigan has the longest freshwater coastline of any U.S. political subdivision, measuring 3,288 miles.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The state ranks second behind Alaska in water coverage by square miles and first in percentage, with approximately 42%, and it also contains 64,980 inland lakes and ponds.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Great Lakes region has largely been inhabited for thousands of years by Indigenous peoples such as the Ojibwe, Odawa, Potawatomi, and Wyandot.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Some people contend that the region's name is derived from the Ojibwe word ᒥᓯᑲᒥ (*mishigami*), meaning "large water" or "large lake".
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Others say that it comes from the Mishiiken Tribe of Mackinac Island, also called Michinemackinawgo by Ottawa historian Andrew Blackbird, whose surrounding lands were referred to as Mishiiken-imakinakom, later shortened to Michilimackinac.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In the 17th century, French explorers claimed the area for New France.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] French settlers and Métis established forts and settlements.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] After France's defeat in the French and Indian War in 1762, the area came under British control and later the U.S. following the Treaty of Paris (1783), though control remained disputed with Indigenous tribes until treaties between 1795 and 1842.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The area was part of the larger Northwest Territory; the Michigan Territory was organized in 1805.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan was admitted as the 26th state on January 26, 1837, entering as a free state and quickly developing into an industrial and trade hub that attracted European immigrants, particularly from Finland, Macedonia, and the Netherlands.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In the 1930s, migration from Appalachia and the Great Migration of Black Southerners further shaped the state, especially in Metro Detroit.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan has a diversified economy with a gross state product of $747.371 billion as of Q4 2025, ranking 14th among the 50 states.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Although the state has developed a diverse economy, in the early 20th century it became widely known as the center of the U.S. automotive industry, which developed as a major national economic force.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] It is home to the country's three major automobile companies (whose headquarters are all in Metro Detroit).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Once exploited for logging and mining, today the sparsely populated Upper Peninsula is important for tourism because of its abundance of natural resources.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Lower Peninsula is a center of manufacturing, forestry, agriculture, services, and high-tech industry.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] When the first European explorers arrived, the most populous tribes were the Algonquian peoples, which include the Anishinaabe groups of Ojibwe, Odaawaa/Odawa (Ottawa), and the Boodewaadamii/Bodéwadmi (Potawatomi).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The three nations coexisted peacefully as part of a loose confederation called the Council of Three Fires.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Ojibwe, whose numbers are estimated to have been at least 35,000, were the largest.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Ojibwe Indians (also known as Chippewa in the U.S.), an Anishinaabe tribe, were established in Michigan's Upper Peninsula and northern and central Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Bands also inhabited Ontario and southern Manitoba, Canada; and northern Wisconsin, and northern and north-central Minnesota.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Smaller groups of Algonquian Indians like the Noquet in the Upper Peninsula were present for thousands of years but subsequently absorbed by neighboring tribes before and during European contact.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Ottawa Indians lived primarily south of the Straits of Mackinac in northern, western, and southern Michigan, but also in southern Ontario, northern Ohio, and eastern Wisconsin.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Potawatomi were in southern and western Michigan, in addition to northern and central Indiana, northern Illinois, southern Wisconsin, and southern Ontario.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Other Algonquian tribes in Michigan, in the south and east, were the Mascouten, the Menominee, the Miami, the Sac (or Sauk), and the Meskwaki (Fox).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Wyandot were an Iroquoian-speaking people in this area; they were historically known as the Huron by the French, and were the historical adversaries of the Iroquois Confederation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] French *voyageurs* and *coureurs des bois* explored and settled in Michigan in the 17th century.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The first Europeans to reach what became Michigan were those of Étienne Brûlé's expedition in 1622.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The first permanent European settlement was founded in 1668 on the site where Père Jacques Marquette established Sault Ste.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Marie, Michigan, as a base for Catholic missions.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Missionaries in 1671–75 founded outlying stations at Saint Ignace and Marquette.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Jesuit missionaries were well received by the area's Indian populations, with few difficulties or hostilities.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In 1679, Robert Cavelier, Sieur de la Salle built Fort Miami at present-day St.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In 1691, the French established a trading post and Fort St.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Joseph River at the present-day city of Niles.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In 1701, French explorer and army officer Antoine de la Mothe Cadillac founded Fort Pontchartrain du Détroit or "Fort Pontchartrain on-the-Strait" on the strait, known as the Detroit River, between lakes St.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Cadillac had convinced Louis XIV's chief minister, Louis Phélypeaux, Comte de Pontchartrain, that a permanent community there would strengthen French control over the upper Great Lakes and discourage British aspirations.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The hundred soldiers and workers who accompanied Cadillac built a fort enclosing one arpent (about 0.85 acres (3,400 m2), the equivalent of just under 200 feet (61 m) per side) and named it Fort Pontchartrain.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Cadillac's wife, Marie Thérèse Guyon, soon moved to Detroit, becoming one of the first European women to settle in what was considered the wilderness of Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The town quickly became a major fur-trading and shipping post.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The *Église de Saint-Anne* (Catholic Church of Saint Anne) was founded the same year.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] While the original building does not survive, the congregation remains active.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Cadillac later departed to serve as the French governor of Louisiana from 1710 to 1716.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] French attempts to consolidate the fur trade led to the Fox Wars, in which the Meskwaki (Fox) and their allies fought the French and their Native allies.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] At the same time, the French strengthened Fort Michilimackinac at the Straits of Mackinac to better control their lucrative fur-trading empire.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] By the mid-18th century, the French also occupied forts at present-day Niles and Sault Ste.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Marie, though most of the rest of the region remained unsettled by Europeans.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] France offered free land to attract families to Detroit, which grew to 800 people in 1765.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] It was the largest city between Montreal and New Orleans.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] French settlers also established small farms south of the Detroit River opposite the fort, near a Jesuit mission and Huron village.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] From 1660 until the end of French rule, Michigan was part of the Royal Province of New France.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In 1760, Montreal fell to the British forces, ending the French and Indian War (1754–1763), the North American front of the Seven Years' War in Europe.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Under the 1763 Treaty of Paris, Michigan and the rest of New France east of the Mississippi River were ceded by defeated France to Great Britain.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] After the Quebec Act was passed in 1774, Michigan became part of the British Province of Quebec.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] By 1778, Detroit's population reached 2,144 and it was the third-largest city in Quebec province.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] During the American Revolutionary War, Detroit was an important British supply center.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Most of the inhabitants were French-Canadians or American Indians, many of whom had been allied with the French because of long trading ties.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Because of imprecise cartography and unclear language defining the boundaries in the 1783 Treaty of Paris, the British retained control of Detroit and Michigan after the American Revolution.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] When Quebec split into Lower and Upper Canada in 1791, Michigan was part of Kent County, Upper Canada.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] It held its first democratic elections in August 1792 to send delegates to the new provincial parliament at Newark (now Niagara-on-the-Lake).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Under terms negotiated in the 1794 Jay Treaty, Britain withdrew from Detroit and Michilimackinac in 1796.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] It retained control of territory east and south of the Detroit River, which are now included in Ontario, Canada.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Questions remained over the boundary for many years, and the United States did not have uncontested control of the Upper Peninsula and Drummond Island until 1818 and 1847, respectively.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] During the War of 1812, the commander of the Army of the Northwest, Brigadier General William Hull, surrendered Detroit and the Michigan Territory to the British after a nearly bloodless siege in August 1812.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] An American attempt to retake British-occupied Michigan Territory in January 1813 resulted in a severe American defeat at the Battle of Frenchtown.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] This battle, still ranked as the bloodiest ever fought in the state, had the highest number of American casualties of any battle of the war.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan was retaken by the Americans in September 1813 after the British abandoned Detroit following the Battle of Lake Erie.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Forces led by Major General William Henry Harrison reoccupied Detroit and launched an invasion of Upper Canada which culminated in a British defeat at the Battle of the Thames.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The more northerly areas of Michigan such as Fort Mackinac were held by the British until the 1815 Treaty of Ghent restored the old boundaries.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] A number of forts, including Fort Wayne, were built by the United States in Michigan during the 19th century out of fears of renewed fighting with Britain.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The population grew slowly until the opening in 1825 of the Erie Canal through the Mohawk Valley in New York, connecting the Great Lakes to the Hudson River and New York City.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The new route attracted a large influx of settlers to the Michigan territory.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] They worked as farmers, lumbermen, shipbuilders, and merchants and shipped out grain, lumber, and iron ore.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] By the 1830s, Michigan had 30,000 residents, more than enough to apply and qualify for statehood.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] A constitutional convention of assent was held to lead the territory to statehood.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In October 1835 the people approved the constitution of 1835, thereby forming a state government.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Congressional recognition was delayed pending resolution of a boundary dispute with Ohio known as the Toledo War.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Congress awarded the "Toledo Strip" to Ohio.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan received the western part of the Upper Peninsula as a concession and formally entered the Union as a free state on January 26, 1837.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Upper Peninsula proved to be a rich source of lumber, iron, and copper.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan led the nation in lumber production from the 1850s to the 1880s.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Railroads became a major engine of growth from the 1850s onward, with Detroit the chief hub.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The first statewide meeting of the Republican Party took place on July 6, 1854, in Jackson, Michigan, where the party adopted its platform.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The state was predominantly Republican until the 1930s, reflecting the political continuity of migrants from across the Northern Tier of New England and New York.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan made a significant contribution to the Union in the American Civil War and sent more than forty regiments of volunteers to the federal armies.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan's economy underwent a transformation at the turn of the 20th century.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Olds, John and Horace Dodge, Henry Leland, David Dunbar Buick, Henry Joy, Charles King, and Henry Ford, provided the concentration of engineering know-how and technological enthusiasm to develop the automotive industry.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Ford's development of the moving assembly line in Highland Park marked a new era in transportation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Like the steamship and railroad, mass production of automobiles was a far-reaching development.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] More than the forms of public transportation, the affordable automobile transformed private life.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Automobile production became the major industry of Detroit and Michigan, and permanently altered the socioeconomic life of the United States and much of the world.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] With the growth, the auto industry created jobs in Detroit that attracted immigrants from Europe and migrants from across the United States, including both blacks and whites from the rural South.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] By 1920, Detroit was the fourth-largest city in the U.S.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Residential housing was in short supply, and it took years for the market to catch up with the population boom.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] By the 1930s, so many immigrants had arrived that more than 30 languages were spoken in the public schools, and ethnic communities celebrated in annual heritage festivals.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Over the years immigrants and migrants contributed greatly to Detroit's diverse urban culture, including popular music trends.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The influential Motown Sound of the 1960s was led by a variety of individual singers and groups.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Grand Rapids, the second-largest city in Michigan, also became an important center of manufacturing.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Since 1838, the city has been noted for its furniture industry.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In the 21st century, it is home to five of the world's leading office furniture companies.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Grand Rapids is home to a number of major companies including Steelcase, Amway, and Meijer.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Grand Rapids is also an important center for GE Aviation Systems.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan held its first United States presidential primary election in 1910.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] With its rapid growth in industry, it was an important center of industry-wide union organizing, such as the rise of the United Auto Workers.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In 1920 WWJ (AM) in Detroit became the first radio station in the United States to regularly broadcast commercial programs.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Throughout that decade, some of the country's largest and most ornate skyscrapers were built in the city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Particularly noteworthy are the Fisher Building, Cadillac Place, and the Guardian Building, each of which has been designated as a National Historic Landmark (NHL).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In 1927 a school bombing took place in Clinton County.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Bath School disaster resulted in the deaths of 38 schoolchildren and constitutes the deadliest mass murder in a school in U.S. history.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan converted much of its manufacturing to satisfy defense needs during World War II; it manufactured 10.9% of the United States military armaments produced during the war, ranking second (behind New York) among the 48 states.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Detroit continued to expand through the 1950s, at one point doubling its population in a decade.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] After World War II, housing was developed in suburban areas outside city cores to meet demand for residences.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The federal government subsidized the construction of interstate highways, which were intended to strengthen military access, but also allowed commuters and business traffic to travel the region more easily.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Since 1960, modern advances in the auto industry have led to increased automation, high-tech industry, and increased suburban growth.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Longstanding tensions in Detroit culminated in the Twelfth Street riot in July 1967.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] During the late 1970s and the early 1980s, increasing fuel costs and other factors made significantly more global competition and recession among families.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan lost a significant amount of population due to global competition and the dramatic unavailability of manufacturing jobs.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Meanwhile, Michigan had increased use of technology, specifically when the IBM Personal Computer started selling in the state, in which became mostly used at work.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan became the leading auto-producing state in the U.S., with the industry primarily located throughout the Midwestern United States; Ontario, Canada; and the Southern United States.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] With almost ten million residents in 2010, Michigan is a large and influential state, ranking tenth in population among the fifty states.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Detroit is the centrally located metropolitan area of the Great Lakes megalopolis and the second-largest metropolitan area in the U.S.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] (after Chicago) linking the Great Lakes system.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Metro Detroit area in Southeast Michigan is the state's largest metropolitan area (roughly 50% of the population resides there) and the eleventh largest in the United States.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Grand Rapids metropolitan area in Western Michigan is the state's fastest-growing metro area, with more than 1.3 million residents as of 2006.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan consists of two peninsulas separated by the Straits of Mackinac.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The 45th parallel north runs through the state, marked by highway signs and the Polar-Equator Trail— along a line including Mission Point Light near Traverse City, the towns of Gaylord and Alpena in the Lower Peninsula and Menominee in the Upper Peninsula.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] With the exception of two tiny areas drained by the Mississippi River by way of the Wisconsin River in the Upper Peninsula and by way of the Kankakee-Illinois River in the Lower Peninsula, Michigan is drained by the Great Lakes-St.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Lawrence watershed and is the only state with the majority of its land thus drained.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] No point in the state is more than six miles (9.7 km) from a natural water source or more than 85 miles (137 km) from a Great Lakes shoreline.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Great Lakes that border Michigan from east to west are Lake Erie, Lake Huron, Lake Michigan and Lake Superior.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Clair, a smaller lake that is part of the Great Lakes system.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The state is bounded on the south by the states of Ohio and Indiana, sharing land and water boundaries with both.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The heavily forested Upper Peninsula is relatively mountainous in the west.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Porcupine Mountains, which are part of one of the oldest mountain chains in the world, rise to an altitude of almost 2,000 feet (610 m) above sea level and form the watershed between the streams flowing into Lake Superior and Lake Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The surface on either side of this range is rugged.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The state's highest point, in the Huron Mountains northwest of Marquette, is Mount Arvon at 1,979 feet (603 m).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The peninsula is as large as Connecticut, Delaware, Massachusetts, and Rhode Island combined but has fewer than 330,000 inhabitants.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The people are sometimes called "Yoopers" (from "U.P.'ers"), and their speech (the "Yooper dialect") has been heavily influenced by the numerous Scandinavian and Canadian immigrants who settled the area during the lumbering and mining boom of the late 19th century.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Lower Peninsula is shaped like a mitten and many residents hold up a hand to depict where they are from.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] It is 277 miles (446 km) long from north to south and 195 miles (314 km) from east to west and occupies nearly two-thirds of the state's land area.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The surface of the peninsula is generally level, broken by conical hills and glacial moraines usually not more than a few hundred feet tall.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] It is divided by a low water divide running north and south.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The larger portion of the state is on the west of this and gradually slopes toward Lake Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The highest point in the Lower Peninsula is either Briar Hill at 1,705 feet (520 m), or one of several points nearby in the vicinity of Cadillac.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The lowest point is the surface of Lake Erie at 571 feet (174 m).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The geographic orientation of Michigan's peninsulas makes for a long distance between the ends of the state.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Ironwood, in the far western Upper Peninsula, lies 630 miles (1,010 kilometers) by highway from Lambertville in the Lower Peninsula's southeastern corner.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The geographic isolation of the Upper Peninsula from Michigan's political and population centers makes the region culturally and economically distinct.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Frequent attempts to establish the Upper Peninsula as its own state have failed to gain traction.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] A feature of Michigan that gives it the distinct shape of a mitten is the Thumb, which projects into Lake Huron, forming Saginaw Bay.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Numerous lakes and marshes mark both peninsulas, and the coast is much indented.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The primary indentations of the Upper Peninsula include Keweenaw Bay and Whitefish Bay, along Lake Superior, Big and Little Bays de Noc along Lake Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In the Lower Peninsula, Grand Traverse and Little Traverse Bays are indentations along Lake Michigan, and Thunder and Saginaw Bays are indentations along Lake Huron.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan has the second longest shoreline of any state—3,288 miles (5,292 km), including 1,056 miles (1,699 km) of island shoreline.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The state has numerous large islands, the principal ones being the North Manitou and South Manitou, Beaver, and Fox groups in Lake Michigan; Isle Royale and Grande Isle in Lake Superior; Marquette, Bois Blanc, and Mackinac islands in Lake Huron; and Neebish, Sugar, and Drummond islands in St.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan has about 150 lighthouses, the most of any U.S. state.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The first lighthouses in Michigan were built between 1818 and 1822.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] They were built to project light at night and to serve as a landmark during the day to safely guide the passenger ships and freighters traveling the Great Lakes (see: lighthouses in the United States).
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The state's rivers are generally small, short and shallow, and few are navigable.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The principal ones include the Detroit River, St.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Clair River which connect the Great Lakes; the Au Sable, Cheboygan, and Saginaw, which flow into Lake Huron; the Ontonagon, and Tahquamenon, which flow into Lake Superior; and the St.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Joseph, Kalamazoo, Grand, Muskegon, Manistee, and Escanaba, which flow into Lake Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The state has 11,037 inland lakes—totaling 1,305 square miles (3,380 km2) of inland water—in addition to 38,575 square miles (99,910 km2) of Great Lakes waters.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] No point in Michigan is more than six miles (9.7 km) from an inland lake or more than 85 miles (137 km) from one of the Great Lakes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The state is home to several areas maintained by the National Park Service including: Isle Royale National Park, in Lake Superior, about 30 miles (48 km) southeast of Thunder Bay, Ontario.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Other national protected areas in the state include: Keweenaw National Historical Park, Pictured Rocks National Lakeshore, Sleeping Bear Dunes National Lakeshore, Huron National Forest, Manistee National Forest, Hiawatha National Forest, Ottawa National Forest and Father Marquette National Memorial.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The largest section of the North Country National Scenic Trail passes through Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] With 78 state parks, 19 state recreation areas, and six state forests, Michigan has the largest state park and state forest system of any state.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan has a continental climate with two distinct regions.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The southern and central parts of the Lower Peninsula (south of Saginaw Bay and from the Grand Rapids area southward) have a warmer climate (Köppen climate classification *Dfa*) with hot summers and cold winters.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The northern part of the Lower Peninsula and the entire Upper Peninsula has a more severe climate (Köppen *Dfb*), with warm, but shorter summers and longer, cold to very cold winters.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Some parts of the state average high temperatures below freezing from December through February, and into early March in the far northern parts.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] During the winter through the middle of February, the state is frequently subjected to heavy lake-effect snow.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The state averages from 30 to 40 inches (76 to 102 cm) of precipitation annually; however, some areas in the northern lower peninsula and the upper peninsula average almost 160 inches (4,100 mm) of snowfall per year.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan's highest recorded temperature is 112 °F (44 °C) at Mio on July 13, 1936, and the coldest recorded temperature is −51 °F (−46 °C) at Vanderbilt on February 9, 1934.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The state averages 30 days of thunderstorm activity per year.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] These can be severe, especially in the southern part of the state.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The state averages 17 tornadoes per year, which are more common in the state's extreme southern section.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Portions of the southern border have been almost as vulnerable historically as states further west and in Tornado Alley.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] For this reason, many communities in the very southern portions of the state have tornado sirens to warn residents of approaching tornadoes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Farther north, in Central Michigan, Northern Michigan, and the Upper Peninsula, tornadoes are rare.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The geological formation of the state is greatly varied, with the Michigan Basin being the most major formation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Primary boulders are found over the entire surface of the Upper Peninsula (being principally of primitive origin), while Secondary deposits cover the entire Lower Peninsula.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Upper Peninsula exhibits Lower Silurian sandstones, limestones, copper and iron bearing rocks, corresponding to the Huronian system of Canada.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The central portion of the Lower Peninsula contains coal measures and rocks of the Pennsylvanian period.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Devonian and sub-Carboniferous deposits are scattered over the entire state.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan rarely experiences earthquakes, and those that it does experience are generally smaller ones that do not cause significant damage.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] A 4.6-magnitude earthquake struck in August 1947.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Geological Survey's National Earthquake Information Center.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] No major damage or injuries were reported, according to then-Governor Rick Snyder's office.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] State government is decentralized among three tiers—statewide, county and township.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Counties are administrative divisions of the state, and townships are administrative divisions of a county.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Both of them exercise state government authority, localized to meet the particular needs of their jurisdictions, as provided by state law.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Cities, state universities, and villages are vested with home rule powers of varying degrees.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Home rule cities can generally do anything not prohibited by law.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The fifteen state universities have broad power and can do anything within the parameters of their status as educational institutions that is not prohibited by the state constitution.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Villages, by contrast, have limited home rule and are not completely autonomous from the county and township in which they are located.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] There are two types of township in Michigan: *general law* township and *charter*.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Charter township status was created by the Legislature in 1947 and grants additional powers and stream-lined administration in order to provide greater protection against annexation by a city.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] As of April 2001, there were 127 charter townships in Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In general, charter townships have many of the same powers as a city but without the same level of obligations.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] For example, a charter township can have its own fire department, water and sewer department, police department, and so on—just like a city—but it is not *required* to have those things, whereas cities *must* provide those services.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Charter townships can opt to use county-wide services instead, such as deputies from the county sheriff's office instead of a home-based force of ordinance officers.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Since the 1800 U.S. census, Michigan has experienced relatively positive and stable population growth trends; beginning with a population of 3,757, the 2010 census recorded 9,883,635 residents.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] At the 2020 United States census, its population was 10,077,331, an increase of 2.03% since 2010's tabulation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] According to the United States Census Bureau, it is the third-most populous state in the Midwest and its East North Central subregion, behind Ohio and Illinois.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The center of population of Michigan is in Shiawassee County, in the southeastern corner of the civil township of Bennington, which is northwest of the village of Morrice.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] According to the American Immigration Council in 2019, an estimated 6.8% of Michiganders were immigrants, while 3.8% were native-born U.S. citizens with at least one immigrant parent.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Numbering approximately 678,255 according to the 2019 survey, the majority of Michigander immigrants came from Mexico (11.5%), India (11.3%), Iraq (7.5%), China (5.3%), and Canada (5.3%); the primary occupations of its immigrants were technology, agriculture, and healthcare.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Among its immigrant cohort, there were 108,105 undocumented immigrants, making up 15.9% of the total immigrant population.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 8,206 homeless people in Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Since colonial European and American settlement, the majority of Michigan's population has been predominantly non-Hispanic or non-Latino white; Americans of European descent live throughout every county in the state, and most of Metro Detroit.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Large European American groups include those of German, British, Irish, Polish and Belgian ancestry.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Scandinavian and Finnish Americans have a notable presence in the Upper Peninsula.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Western Michigan is known for its Dutch heritage, especially in Holland and metropolitan Grand Rapids.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Black and African Americans—coming to Detroit and other northern cities in the Great Migration of the early 20th century—have formed a majority of the population in Detroit and other cities including Flint and Benton Harbor.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Since the 2021 census estimates—while Detroit was still the largest city in Michigan with a majority black population—it was no longer the largest black-majority city in the U.S., citing crime and higher-paying jobs given to whites.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] As of 2007, about 300,000 people in Southeastern Michigan trace their descent from the Middle East and Asia.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Dearborn has a sizeable Arab American community, with many Assyrians, and Lebanese who immigrated for jobs in the auto industry in the 1920s, along with more recent Yemenis and Iraqis.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Dearborn also houses an Armenian minority population, initially consisting of entirely young men.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] There is a statue of Komitas, an Armenian priest and composer, standing on Jefferson Avenue, in Detroit.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] As of 2007, almost 8,000 Hmong people lived in the state of Michigan, about double their 1999 presence in the state.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Most lived in northeastern Detroit, but they had been increasingly moving to Pontiac and Warren.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] By 2015, the number of Hmong in the Detroit city limits had significantly declined.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Lansing hosts a statewide Hmong New Year Festival.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Hmong community also had a prominent portrayal in the 2008 film *Gran Torino*, which was set in Detroit.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] As of 2015, 80% of Michigan's Japanese population lived in the counties of Macomb, Oakland, Washtenaw, and Wayne in the Detroit and Ann Arbor areas.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] As of April 2013, the largest Japanese national population is in Novi, with 2,666 Japanese residents, and the next largest populations are respectively in Ann Arbor, West Bloomfield Township, Farmington Hills, and Battle Creek.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The state has 481 Japanese employment facilities providing 35,554 local jobs.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] 391 of them are in Southeast Michigan, providing 20,816 jobs, and the 90 in other regions in the state provide 14,738 jobs.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Japanese Direct Investment Survey of the Consulate-General of Japan, Detroit stated more than 2,208 additional Japanese residents were employed in the State of Michigan as of 1 October 2012, than in 2011.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] During the 1990s, the Japanese population of Michigan experienced an increase, and many Japanese people with children moved to particular areas for their proximity to Japanese grocery stores and high-performing schools.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In total, 8.89% (830,281) of Michigan's population age five and older spoke a mother language other than English.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Since 2021, 90.1% of residents aged five and older spoke only English at home, and Spanish was the second-most spoken language with 2.9% of the population speaking it.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Following British and French colonization of the region surrounding Michigan, Christianity became the dominant religion, with Roman Catholicism historically being the largest single Christian group for the state.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Until the 19th century, the Roman Catholic Church was the only organized religious group in Michigan, reflecting the territory's French colonial roots.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Anne's parish, established in 1701 by Antoine de la Mothe Cadillac, is the second-oldest Roman Catholic parish in the United States.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] On March 8, 1833, the Holy See formally established a diocese in the Michigan territory, which included all of Michigan, Wisconsin, Minnesota, and the Dakotas east of the Mississippi River.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] When Michigan became a state in 1837, the boundary of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Detroit was redrawn to coincide with that of the state; the other dioceses were later carved out from the Detroit Diocese but remain part of the Ecclesiastical Province of Detroit.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Several Native American religions have been practiced in Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In 2020, there were 1,492,732 adherents of Roman Catholicism.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] There's also a significant Independent Catholic presence in Metro Detroit, including the Ecumenical Catholic Church of Christ established by Archbishop Karl Rodig; the see of this church operates in a former Roman Catholic parish church.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] With the introduction of Protestantism to the state, it began to form the largest collective Christian group.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In 2010, the Association of Religion Data Archives reported the largest Protestant denomination was the United Methodist Church with 228,521 adherents; followed by the Lutheran Church–Missouri Synod with 219,618, and the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America with 120,598 adherents.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Christian Reformed Church in North America had almost 100,000 members and more than 230 congregations in Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Reformed Church in America had 76,000 members and 154 congregations in the state.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] By the 2020 study, non- and inter-denominational Protestant churches formed the largest Protestant group in Michigan, numbering 508,904.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Lutheran Church–Missouri Synod grew to become the second-largest single Christian denomination, and United Methodists declined to being the third-largest.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The Lutheran Protestant tradition was introduced by German and Scandinavian immigrants.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Altogether, Baptists numbered 321,581 between the National Missionary Baptists, National Baptists, American Baptists, Southern Baptists, National Baptists of America, Progressive National Baptists, and Full Gospel Baptists; black Baptists formed the largest constituency.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] In the same 2010 survey, Jewish adherents in the state of Michigan were estimated at 44,382, and Muslims at 120,351.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] The first Jewish synagogue in the state was Temple Beth El, founded by twelve German Jewish families in Detroit in 1850.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Islam was introduced by immigrants from the Near East during the 20th century.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Michigan is home to the largest mosque in North America, the Islamic Center of America in Dearborn.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p01] Battle Creek, Michigan, is also the birthplace of the Seventh-day Adventist Church, which was founded on May 21, 1863.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan is among the wealthiest regions in the world.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] As of 2025, its gross state product (GSP) stands at $747.371 billion ($72,898 per capita), ranking 14th among the 50 U.S. states.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan's nominal GDP is larger than that of every nation in Africa and all but Brazil in South America.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Its nominal per capita GDP exceeds all but two nations in the European Union.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] When adjusted for regional price parities, Michigan's per capita GDP is significantly higher than the European average, surpassing the figures of France, Italy, and the United Kingdom.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] As of December 2025, the state recorded total non-farm employment of 4,543,300 across 315,965 employer establishments.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan is home to 15 Fortune 500 companies as of 2024, and in 2025 alone, 152,800 new businesses were formed.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The state's 983,079 small businesses represent 99.6% of all businesses and employ 47.7% of the state's workforce.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] As of May 2025, Michigan had an unemployment rate of 5.4%.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The state's five largest employment sectors are education and health services; professional and business services; manufacturing; trade, transportation, and utilities; and leisure and hospitality.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] In output, the five largest sectors are manufacturing, followed by financial services; professional and business services; education and health services; and trade, transportation, and utilities.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] As the busiest international border crossing in North America by trade volume, the Detroit–Windsor crossing plays a pivotal role in the global supply chain, handling approximately one third of all Canada–U.S. trade.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Additionally, the Soo Locks, which connect Lake Superior to the lower Great Lakes, is the world's busiest lock system by tonnage, with 80 million tons passing through annually.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan's economy is heavily reliant on trade, with international commerce accounting for roughly 42% of the state's economy; Canada remains its largest trading partner.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Manufacturing, particularly the automotive industry, generates one seventh of the state's economy.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] In 2023, Michigan exported $81 billion worth of goods.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Transportation equipment, including motor vehicles and parts, is the state's top export, accounting for 45% of all exports in 2022.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan ranks first in the nation for the export of motor vehicles and parts.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan's personal income tax is a flat rate of 4.25%.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] In addition, 24 cities impose income taxes; rates are set at 1% for residents and 0.5% for non-residents in all but four cities.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan's state sales tax is 6%, though items such as food and medication are exempted.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Property taxes are assessed on the local level, but every property owner's local assessment contributes six mills (a rate of $6 per $1000 of property value) to the statutory State Education Tax.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Property taxes are appealable to local boards of review and need the approval of the local electorate to exceed millage rates prescribed by state law and local charters.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] In 2011, the state repealed its business tax and replaced it with a 6% corporate income tax which substantially reduced taxes on business.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Article IX of the Constitution of the State of Michigan also provides limitations on how much the state can tax.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] A 6% use tax is levied on goods purchased outside the state (that are brought in and used in state), at parity with the sales tax.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The use tax applies to internet sales/purchases from outside Michigan and is equivalent to the sales tax.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] On December 20, 2019, Governor Gretchen Whitmer signed a package of bills into law effectively legalizing online gambling activities in Michigan, which allowed commercial and tribal casinos to apply for internet gaming licenses.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] A wide variety of commodity crops, fruits, and vegetables are grown in Michigan, making it second only to California among US states in the diversity of its agriculture.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The state has 54,800 farms utilizing 10,000,000 acres (40,000 km2) of land which sold $6.49 billion worth of products in 2010.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The most valuable agricultural product is milk.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Leading crops include corn, soybeans, flowers, wheat, sugar beets, and potatoes.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Livestock in the state included 78,000 sheep, a million cattle, a million hogs, and more than three million chickens.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Livestock products accounted for 38% of the value of agricultural products while crops accounted for the majority.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan is a leading grower of fruit in the US, including blueberries, tart cherries, apples, grapes, and peaches.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan produces 70 percent of the country's cherries.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Most of these cherries are Montmorency cherries.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Plums, pears, and strawberries are also grown in Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] These fruits are mainly grown in West Michigan due to the moderating effect of Lake Michigan on the climate.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] There is also significant fruit production, especially cherries, but also grapes, apples, and other fruits, in northwest Michigan along Lake Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan produces wines, beers and a multitude of processed food products.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Kellogg's cereal is based in Battle Creek, Michigan and processes many locally grown foods.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Thornapple Valley, Ball Park Franks, Koegel Meat Company, and Hebrew National sausage companies are all based in Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan is home to very fertile land in the Saginaw Valley and Thumb areas.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Products grown there include corn, sugar beets, navy beans, and soybeans.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Sugar beet harvesting usually begins the first of October.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] It takes the sugar factories about five months to process the 3.7 million tons of sugarbeets into 485,000 tons of pure, white sugar.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan's largest sugar refiner, Michigan Sugar Company is the largest east of the Mississippi River and the fourth largest in the nation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan sugar brand names are Pioneer Sugar and the newly incorporated Big Chief Sugar.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Potatoes are grown in Northern Michigan, and corn is dominant in Central Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Alfalfa, cucumbers, and asparagus are also grown.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] As of 2011, Michigan's tourists spent $17.2 billion per year in the state, supporting 193,000 tourism jobs.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan's tourism website ranks among the busiest in the nation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Destinations draw vacationers, hunters, and nature enthusiasts from across the United States and Canada.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan is over 50% forest land, much of it quite remote.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The forests, lakes and thousands of miles of beaches are top attractions.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Event tourism draws large numbers to occasions like the Tulip Time Festival and the National Cherry Festival.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] In 2006, the Michigan State Board of Education mandated all public schools in the state hold their first day of school after Labor Day, in accordance with the new post-Labor Day school law.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] A survey found 70% of all tourism business comes directly from Michigan residents, and the Michigan Hotel, Motel, & Resort Association claimed the shorter summer between school years cut into the annual tourism season.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] However, a bill introduced in 2023 would cancel this requirement, allowing individual districts to decide when their school year should begin.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Tourism in metropolitan Detroit draws visitors to leading attractions, especially The Henry Ford, the Detroit Institute of Arts, the Detroit Zoo, and to sports in Detroit.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Other museums include the Detroit Historical Museum, the Charles H.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Wright Museum of African American History, museums in the Cranbrook Educational Community, and the Arab American National Museum.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The metro area offers four major casinos, MGM Grand Detroit, Hollywood Casino, Motor City, and Caesars Windsor in Windsor, Ontario, Canada; moreover, Detroit is the largest American city and metropolitan region to offer casino resorts.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Hunting and fishing are significant industries in the state.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Charter boats are based in many Great Lakes cities to fish for salmon, trout, walleye, and perch.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan ranks first in the nation in licensed hunters (over one million) who contribute $2 billion annually to its economy.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] More than three-quarters of a million hunters participate in white-tailed deer season alone.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Many school districts in rural areas of Michigan cancel school on the opening day of firearm deer season, because of attendance concerns.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan's Department of Natural Resources manages the largest dedicated state forest system in the nation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The forest products industry and recreational users contribute $12 billion and 200,000 associated jobs annually to the state's economy.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Public hiking and hunting access has also been secured in extensive commercial forests.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The state has the highest number of golf courses and registered snowmobiles in the nation.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The state has numerous historical markers, which can themselves become the center of a tour.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The Great Lakes Circle Tour is a designated scenic road system connecting all of the Great Lakes and the St.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] With its position in relation to the Great Lakes and the countless ships that have foundered over the many years they have been used as a transport route for people and bulk cargo, Michigan is a world-class scuba diving destination.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The Michigan Underwater Preserves are 13 underwater areas where wrecks are protected for the benefit of sport divers.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan music is known for three music trends: early punk rock, Motown/soul music and techno music.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Major theaters in Michigan include the Fox Theatre, Music Hall, Gem Theatre, Masonic Temple Theatre, the Detroit Opera House, Fisher Theatre, The Fillmore Detroit, Saint Andrew's Hall, Majestic Theater, and Orchestra Hall.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The Nederlander Organization, the largest controller of Broadway productions in New York City, originated in Detroit.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] Michigan's major-league sports teams include: Detroit Tigers baseball team, Detroit Lions football team, Detroit Red Wings ice hockey team, and the Detroit Pistons men's basketball team.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] All of Michigan's major league teams play in the Metro Detroit area.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The state also has a professional second-tier (USL Championship) soccer team in Detroit City FC, which plays its home games at Keyworth Stadium in Hamtramck, Michigan.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The Pistons played at Detroit's Cobo Arena until 1978 and at the Pontiac Silverdome until 1988 when they moved into The Palace of Auburn Hills.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] In 2017, the team moved to the newly built Little Caesars Arena in downtown Detroit.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The Detroit Lions played at Tiger Stadium in Detroit until 1974, then moved to the Pontiac Silverdome where they played for 27 years between 1975 and 2002 before moving to Ford Field in Detroit in 2002.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The Detroit Tigers played at Tiger Stadium (formerly known as Navin Field and Briggs Stadium) from 1912 to 1999.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] The Red Wings played at Olympia Stadium before moving to Joe Louis Arena in 1979.
[src:national-center-for-manufacturing-sciences/michigan-p02] They later moved to Little Caesars Arena to join the Pistons as tenants in 2017.
